highlight's easy.

00:03:50.930 --> 00:03:53.138
That's we won the Stanley
Cup with the Boston Bruins.

00:03:53.138 --> 00:03:58.380
I mean, that was far and away
the most amazing sporting

00:03:58.380 --> 00:04:00.870
experience, and probably
even more amazing

00:04:00.870 --> 00:04:02.160
because I had lost it.

00:04:02.160 --> 00:04:06.150
In Calgary, we lost in the
seventh game of the Stanley Cup

00:04:06.150 --> 00:04:08.430
final to the Tampa
Bay Lightning,

00:04:08.430 --> 00:04:10.410
which quite literally--

00:04:10.410 --> 00:04:12.000
I'm almost embarrassed
to say, but I

00:04:12.000 --> 00:04:14.910
would wake up at night
years later just like,

00:04:14.910 --> 00:04:18.300
oh, like, what if?

00:04:18.300 --> 00:04:22.570
It's like just post-traumatic
about that series.

00:04:22.570 --> 00:04:25.260
So winning it was not only
great because we won it,

00:04:25.260 --> 00:04:28.020
but it actually erased all
those demons from losing it.

00:04:28.020 --> 00:04:31.234
So far and away, the highlight.

00:04:31.234 --> 00:04:31.900
SPEAKER 1: Yeah.

00:04:31.900 --> 00:04:35.760
And Kate, a little bit about
some of the iconic brands

00:04:35.760 --> 00:04:39.060
you've worked with, like, what
has that experience been like,

00:04:39.060 --> 00:04:41.850
just reaching, becoming a
professional photographer,

00:04:41.850 --> 00:04:44.550
getting asked to work with
Disney's and Kellogg's and

00:04:44.550 --> 00:04:45.902
NBC's?

00:04:45.902 --> 00:04:47.610
KATE T. PARKER: I
mean, it's crazy to me,

00:04:47.610 --> 00:04:52.780
because, like I said, I
did not go to photo school.

00:04:52.780 --> 00:04:53.280
You know?

00:04:53.280 --> 00:04:55.920
And it just started, and
it still remains, like,

00:04:55.920 --> 00:04:59.100
a one-person business
in my studio, which

00:04:59.100 --> 00:05:01.050
is in the basement of
my house in Atlanta.

00:05:01.050 --> 00:05:04.410
So it's not like, oh, of
course, Disney's calling.

00:05:04.410 --> 00:05:06.300
Of course, you know?

00:05:06.300 --> 00:05:09.030
I literally remember
getting a phone call

00:05:09.030 --> 00:05:10.470
from somebody at Disney.

00:05:10.470 --> 00:05:11.970
I was in the car,
and I thought it

00:05:11.970 --> 00:05:16.090
was a friend calling as a joke.

00:05:16.090 --> 00:05:19.200
And I was like, "the" Disney?

00:05:19.200 --> 00:05:20.700
I had to double-check.

00:05:20.700 --> 00:05:24.360
But I really enjoy
it, because I'm

00:05:24.360 --> 00:05:27.660
so passionate about the message
that my book puts forward

00:05:27.660 --> 00:05:29.430
and that my image
has put forward.

00:05:29.430 --> 00:05:32.310
And when larger companies
with a greater platform

00:05:32.310 --> 00:05:34.380
want to share that same
message of empowerment

00:05:34.380 --> 00:05:38.130
for girls and self-acceptance,
I'm 100% on board.

00:05:38.130 --> 00:05:39.840
And I'm so glad,
just because I feel

00:05:39.840 --> 00:05:43.070
like there's so much
of what our girls see,

00:05:43.070 --> 00:05:47.266
and women see, is not real
and doesn't reflect what

00:05:47.266 --> 00:05:48.390
they look like or act like.

00:05:48.390 --> 00:05:51.120
So if we can put
imagery out there

00:05:51.120 --> 00:05:56.170
that is real girls doing real
things and being themselves,

00:05:56.170 --> 00:05:58.240
and if these larger
brands get behind it,

00:05:58.240 --> 00:06:01.380
I'm so excited because I
get to combine what I do

00:06:01.380 --> 00:06:04.454
and what I love to do, but
with just a bigger platform.

00:06:04.454 --> 00:06:05.120
SPEAKER 1: Yeah.

00:06:05.120 --> 00:06:06.411
So that's a perfect transition.

00:06:06.411 --> 00:06:07.900
I want you to explain--

00:06:07.900 --> 00:06:09.990
we have one of the
most interesting photos

00:06:09.990 --> 00:06:12.510
that you've shared, so
if you could tell us

00:06:12.510 --> 00:06:13.699
the story behind this photo.

00:06:13.699 --> 00:06:14.490
KATE T. PARKER: Oh.

00:06:14.490 --> 00:06:17.040
So OK, this is my
older daughter, Ella.

00:06:17.040 --> 00:06:20.280
And she was-- I think
she was nine at the time,

00:06:20.280 --> 00:06:24.672
and she was getting ready
to do her first triathlon.

00:06:24.672 --> 00:06:26.130
So if you've ever
done a triathlon,

00:06:26.130 --> 00:06:28.200
you go to the race
expo the day before,

00:06:28.200 --> 00:06:29.580
and they give you everything.

00:06:29.580 --> 00:06:33.050
You get your bike set up,
and you get your swim cap,

00:06:33.050 --> 00:06:34.290
your race number.

00:06:34.290 --> 00:06:36.434
But it's super intimidating
because everybody there

00:06:36.434 --> 00:06:38.100
looks like they know
what they're doing.

00:06:38.100 --> 00:06:44.010
And she came back, and
she had all her stuff,

00:06:44.010 --> 00:06:45.810
and she was like,
Mom, I can't do it.

00:06:45.810 --> 00:06:47.850
I'm not ready, I
don't want to do it.

00:06:47.850 --> 00:06:50.330
And I was like,
get your stuff on,

00:06:50.330 --> 00:06:52.080
and come meet me
downstairs in the studio.

00:06:52.080 --> 00:06:54.360
And I snapped maybe
three pictures.

00:06:54.360 --> 00:06:56.790
I said to her, show
me your toughest look.

00:06:56.790 --> 00:06:58.087
Show me how brave you are.

00:06:58.087 --> 00:07:00.420
And I literally took the
camera and I flipped it around.

00:07:00.420 --> 00:07:03.300
And I said, don't you think
this girl can do a triathlon?

00:07:03.300 --> 00:07:06.360
And she was like,
oh, yeah, I think so.

00:07:06.360 --> 00:07:09.370
I showed her who she was,
she just didn't believe it.

00:07:09.370 --> 00:07:12.180
And she went out the next
day and she killed it.

00:07:12.180 --> 00:07:15.510
And one of the reasons that I
love this picture so much is

00:07:15.510 --> 00:07:17.910
it's the cover of our book.

00:07:17.910 --> 00:07:20.400
And it just shows--

00:07:20.400 --> 00:07:21.210
I had no idea.

00:07:21.210 --> 00:07:22.230
There was no book at the time.

00:07:22.230 --> 00:07:23.104
There was no message.

00:07:23.104 --> 00:07:27.120
I just was taking a picture
so she would go do the race.

00:07:27.120 --> 00:07:33.030
And I just love the power in
it and how strong and confident

00:07:33.030 --> 00:07:34.080
she looks.

00:07:34.080 --> 00:07:37.910
And I just love
remembering that story.

00:07:37.910 --> 00:07:38.640
Yeah.

00:07:38.640 --> 00:07:40.890
SPEAKER 1: So we're going
to talk about your parenting

00:07:40.890 --> 00:07:43.170
style and, just in
general, the theme.

00:07:43.170 --> 00:07:45.150
But talk to us a
little bit about how

00:07:45.150 --> 00:07:48.150
your parents influenced you
both getting to the highest

00:07:48.150 --> 00:07:50.790
level of your professions,
and how has that impacted

00:07:50.790 --> 00:07:52.230
your current parenting style.

00:07:52.230 --> 00:07:52.530
KATE T. PARKER: Sure.

00:07:52.530 --> 00:07:53.756
You want to take that one?

00:07:53.756 --> 00:07:54.630
ANDREW FERENCE: Yeah.

00:07:54.630 --> 00:07:58.210
I mean, my parents, neither
of them were big into sports.

00:07:58.210 --> 00:07:59.940
I mean, they were
active and whatnot.

00:07:59.940 --> 00:08:03.880
But my dad did some judo, and
squash, and stuff like that,

00:08:03.880 --> 00:08:05.370
but never hockey.

00:08:05.370 --> 00:08:08.650
But they always supported
whatever I was interested in.

00:08:08.650 --> 00:08:11.220
And the only thing
that they ever demanded

00:08:11.220 --> 00:08:13.490
was that, if you start
something, you finish it.

00:08:13.490 --> 00:08:15.990
And you do your absolute best,
like you put your most effort

00:08:15.990 --> 00:08:16.490
into it.

00:08:16.490 --> 00:08:19.020
So whether that was
homework, sports, anything.

00:08:19.020 --> 00:08:21.210
And the only time
my dad ever gave me

00:08:21.210 --> 00:08:23.370
any, like, sporting
advice is it'd

00:08:23.370 --> 00:08:28.200
be along the lines of, you know,
we're up 6-0 in a hockey game,

00:08:28.200 --> 00:08:30.240
and on the ride home,
he'd be like, you know,

00:08:30.240 --> 00:08:32.220
I noticed during
the third period

00:08:32.220 --> 00:08:34.039
you kind of relaxed a bit.

00:08:34.039 --> 00:08:36.809
And he's like, that's really
disrespectful to the other team

00:08:36.809 --> 00:08:39.150
to not try your hardest,
even though you're winning.

00:08:39.150 --> 00:08:40.944
Like, you shouldn't goof around.

00:08:40.944 --> 00:08:42.360
You know, so that
kind of approach

00:08:42.360 --> 00:08:46.230
of, always finish a job, do it
properly from start to finish,

00:08:46.230 --> 00:08:48.090
no matter the circumstances.

00:08:48.090 --> 00:08:52.050
You know, his view was, if
he walked into the arena

00:08:52.050 --> 00:08:54.506
and we were up 8-0
or down 8-0, he

00:08:54.506 --> 00:08:56.130
shouldn't be able to
tell by the effort

00:08:56.130 --> 00:08:57.504
that I was putting
in on the ice.

00:08:57.504 --> 00:09:00.990
And so that was always a big
lesson for me and, I think,

00:09:00.990 --> 00:09:04.470
carries over to my
two girls where I just

00:09:04.470 --> 00:09:07.960
want them to enjoy what they're
doing and work really hard.

00:09:07.960 --> 00:09:11.370
And I think that those two
things combined can create

00:09:11.370 --> 00:09:13.010
magic in anything, you know?

00:09:13.010 --> 00:09:16.170
And I don't care what sport
it is or what line of work

00:09:16.170 --> 00:09:18.750
or whatever their interests
are, but you do that

00:09:18.750 --> 00:09:20.977
and you'll have a
pretty good life.

00:09:20.977 --> 00:09:22.560
KATE T. PARKER: That
was great advice.

00:09:22.560 --> 00:09:23.140
Yeah.

00:09:23.140 --> 00:09:23.640
Yeah.

00:09:23.640 --> 00:09:27.720
For me, I grew up playing
soccer, and it 100%

00:09:27.720 --> 00:09:31.950
informed my approach to
everything and my approach

00:09:31.950 --> 00:09:33.750
to parenting, as well.

00:09:33.750 --> 00:09:36.030
My parents never, ever told me--

00:09:36.030 --> 00:09:38.584
I have two older brothers
and an older sister,

00:09:38.584 --> 00:09:39.750
so I'm the youngest of four.

00:09:39.750 --> 00:09:41.520
And my older brothers
all played soccer.

00:09:41.520 --> 00:09:43.140
And my parents never said--

00:09:43.140 --> 00:09:46.770
because at the time, there was
not soccer teams for girls.

00:09:46.770 --> 00:09:48.552
And they never said that.

00:09:48.552 --> 00:09:50.010
They just said,
sure, you can play.

00:09:50.010 --> 00:09:51.290
And I would play with boys.

00:09:51.290 --> 00:09:53.920
And then there became
soccer teams for girls.

00:09:53.920 --> 00:09:55.920
But they never, ever said--

00:09:55.920 --> 00:09:58.980
you know, because I was loud
and kind of in your face.

00:09:58.980 --> 00:10:02.910
And they never said girls are
not supposed to be like that,

00:10:02.910 --> 00:10:04.380
and girls are supposed--

00:10:04.380 --> 00:10:06.000
I had a temper.

00:10:06.000 --> 00:10:09.390
And I mean, they would
try to curb my temper,

00:10:09.390 --> 00:10:12.600
but they never said,
little girls are quiet.

00:10:12.600 --> 00:10:15.030
And I mean, I try to do the
same and pass that along

00:10:15.030 --> 00:10:15.630
to my girls.

00:10:15.630 --> 00:10:18.690
I never thought that,
because of my sex,

00:10:18.690 --> 00:10:20.400
I would be limited by anything.

00:10:20.400 --> 00:10:22.920
And I try to do the
same for my girls,

00:10:22.920 --> 00:10:26.490
that whatever they're
interested in, they can do it.

00:10:26.490 --> 00:10:29.540
Like Andrew said, you
know, as long as you dig in

00:10:29.540 --> 00:10:30.290
and you work hard.

00:10:30.290 --> 00:10:32.550
I don't care what
they want to do.

00:10:32.550 --> 00:10:34.260
It does not have to be sports.

00:10:34.260 --> 00:10:37.050
Alice is 100%
interested in singing.

00:10:37.050 --> 00:10:38.820
And you've just
got to work hard.

00:10:38.820 --> 00:10:41.190
Whatever it is, we
will support you.

00:10:41.190 --> 00:10:42.875
You've just got to work hard.

