up with the idea?

00:11:00.340 --> 00:11:02.800
And where did this spawn from?

00:11:02.800 --> 00:11:05.620
KATE T. PARKER: So for
years, I just shot my girls

00:11:05.620 --> 00:11:06.520
as they were.

00:11:06.520 --> 00:11:09.400
And after maybe
four or five years,

00:11:09.400 --> 00:11:12.280
I was asked to be part of
the gallery show in Atlanta.

00:11:12.280 --> 00:11:15.250
And so I had to cull
through thousands of images

00:11:15.250 --> 00:11:17.050
to find the 20 strongest.

00:11:17.050 --> 00:11:18.940
And at that point,
I was just shooting.

00:11:18.940 --> 00:11:20.020
I wasn't shooting
with a purpose,

00:11:20.020 --> 00:11:21.936
I wasn't shooting with
the idea that there was

00:11:21.936 --> 00:11:23.200
going to a book or a message.

00:11:23.200 --> 00:11:27.100
But looking at the 20 images
that I selected for the gallery

00:11:27.100 --> 00:11:29.860
on the wall, I was like, oh.

00:11:29.860 --> 00:11:31.210
It finally dawned on me.

00:11:31.210 --> 00:11:35.290
I was like, oh, this is about
showing these girls for who

00:11:35.290 --> 00:11:38.567
they are and celebrating
for who they are, which is--

00:11:38.567 --> 00:11:40.150
for my girls and the
girls that I shot

00:11:40.150 --> 00:11:43.870
were dirty, and fearless,
and silly, and emotional.

00:11:43.870 --> 00:11:45.970
They weren't necessarily
smiling for the camera.

00:11:45.970 --> 00:11:53.470
And so that gallery show was
a huge bust, and nothing sold.

00:11:53.470 --> 00:11:55.420
And that was expensive
as a photographer,

00:11:55.420 --> 00:11:58.680
because you pay for your images.

00:11:58.680 --> 00:12:00.910
And to print and
frame 20 images, I--

00:12:00.910 --> 00:12:02.740
first, I got really
disappointed,

00:12:02.740 --> 00:12:05.230
and I was like, oh, I'm
terrible photographer.

00:12:05.230 --> 00:12:07.480
And then my temper
came into play,

00:12:07.480 --> 00:12:11.950
and I got mad because
I did so much work.

00:12:11.950 --> 00:12:14.230
And I really thought that
there was something there,

00:12:14.230 --> 00:12:17.270
and so I sent a few like this.

00:12:17.270 --> 00:12:20.410
I would send this little
grid of images to three blogs

00:12:20.410 --> 00:12:21.220
that I followed.

00:12:21.220 --> 00:12:24.100
They were culture and art
blogs about photography.

00:12:24.100 --> 00:12:27.800
And then it just kind of
went viral from there.

00:12:27.800 --> 00:12:30.402
It went to CNN, the Today
Show, Huffington Post.

00:12:30.402 --> 00:12:32.110
All these places were
writing this story,

00:12:32.110 --> 00:12:36.290
and I was like, oh, that's
not what I intended at all.

00:12:36.290 --> 00:12:39.280
And then the opportunity
from that came to do a book.

00:12:39.280 --> 00:12:41.740
And up until that
point, the series

00:12:41.740 --> 00:12:46.180
was very narrow in terms
of what strong looked like,

00:12:46.180 --> 00:12:48.770
because it looked like my
daughters and their friends.

00:12:48.770 --> 00:12:52.114
So I used the book as an
opportunity to expand.

00:12:52.114 --> 00:12:53.530
I shot girls all
over the country.

00:12:53.530 --> 00:12:56.770
Just really wanted to get
diversity in the message,

00:12:56.770 --> 00:12:59.530
and in the interests, and
in where the girl's from.

00:12:59.530 --> 00:13:03.640
So that's kind of how it
started, just with me having

00:13:03.640 --> 00:13:05.410
a little temper
tantrum that nothing

00:13:05.410 --> 00:13:08.030
had sold in my gallery show.

00:13:08.030 --> 00:13:10.870
SPEAKER 1: And Andrew, I think
you had a little bit different.

00:13:10.870 --> 00:13:12.654
I know you said that
your daughter started

00:13:12.654 --> 00:13:15.070
figure skating, which you would
think, as a hockey player,

00:13:15.070 --> 00:13:16.653
would be great to
be back at the rink.

00:13:16.653 --> 00:13:18.125
But that wasn't
the case, was it?

00:13:18.125 --> 00:13:19.000
ANDREW FERENCE: Yeah.

00:13:19.000 --> 00:13:21.641
I mean, my story's
all over the map.

00:13:21.641 --> 00:13:24.140
I grew up with a sister who was
involved in a lot of sports.

00:13:24.140 --> 00:13:27.084
And I think, to Kate's
experience, she had no limits,

00:13:27.084 --> 00:13:28.000
do whatever she wants.

00:13:28.000 --> 00:13:29.958
But she was really into
dance, and so I kind of

00:13:29.958 --> 00:13:31.330
knew that world.

00:13:31.330 --> 00:13:33.700
And then having my own
daughters, same thing.

00:13:33.700 --> 00:13:36.460
We opened up the books to them,
like try whatever you want--

00:13:36.460 --> 00:13:39.160
multi-sport, multi-interest.

00:13:39.160 --> 00:13:42.190
But both of them
actually did trend

00:13:42.190 --> 00:13:44.950
towards figure skating early on.

00:13:44.950 --> 00:13:47.650
They also loved going
to Disney and getting

00:13:47.650 --> 00:13:50.230
the bippity boppity
boo [INAUDIBLE],,

00:13:50.230 --> 00:13:51.470
the whole nine yards.

00:13:51.470 --> 00:13:53.740
I'm like, all right, I'll
support that, whatever.

00:13:53.740 --> 00:13:55.280
Just kind of same thing.

00:13:55.280 --> 00:13:57.640
You know, I tried to nudge
them one way or another,

00:13:57.640 --> 00:14:00.290
but they determined
their own path.

00:14:00.290 --> 00:14:01.750
So the path was figure skating.

00:14:01.750 --> 00:14:05.950
And the only reason
that sport frustrated me

00:14:05.950 --> 00:14:08.680
was because I would go
and watch their practices,

00:14:08.680 --> 00:14:12.060
and it's an incredibly
athletic sport.

00:14:12.060 --> 00:14:14.020
They'd try over,
and over, and over,

00:14:14.020 --> 00:14:15.640
and fall down, and get up.

00:14:15.640 --> 00:14:19.450
And to finally nail a new
trick would take so much effort

00:14:19.450 --> 00:14:20.560
over weeks, right?

00:14:20.560 --> 00:14:22.930
And bumps, and bruises,
and frustrations.

00:14:22.930 --> 00:14:24.490
And when they would
finally, nail it,

00:14:24.490 --> 00:14:27.100
I was like, man, that's
incredible just how much effort

00:14:27.100 --> 00:14:27.900
went into that.

00:14:27.900 --> 00:14:30.620
And think of all the
lessons that they learned.

00:14:30.620 --> 00:14:34.260
But the kicker was always
the competition day.

00:14:34.260 --> 00:14:36.820
And they had to have
the full makeup.

00:14:36.820 --> 00:14:39.260
They had to have
the shiny dress,

00:14:39.260 --> 00:14:41.770
and they had to smile when
they're doing the routine.

00:14:41.770 --> 00:14:44.230
And that was the part that
just always just got me,

00:14:44.230 --> 00:14:47.350
because you get less
points if you don't smile.

00:14:47.350 --> 00:14:48.809
And I was always
just like, really?

00:14:48.809 --> 00:14:49.308
You know?

00:14:49.308 --> 00:14:51.450
Because after all those
weeks of watching practice,

00:14:51.450 --> 00:14:53.200
and how hard they
worked, and how athletic

00:14:53.200 --> 00:14:55.450
they were, I'm like, what
if they don't want to smile?

00:14:55.450 --> 00:14:57.730
What if they can
just be an athlete

00:14:57.730 --> 00:15:00.010
and be taken at face
value for all the work

00:15:00.010 --> 00:15:01.612
that they put into this?

00:15:01.612 --> 00:15:03.070
So that was always
kind of the rub.

00:15:03.070 --> 00:15:05.680
And then honestly, it
started rubbing them.

00:15:05.680 --> 00:15:09.340
And I didn't sit them down and
tell them about this or rant,

00:15:09.340 --> 00:15:11.870
and they kind of figured
it out for themselves.

00:15:11.870 --> 00:15:15.970
And that kind of, I think,
started getting to them.

00:15:15.970 --> 00:15:18.340
So my oldest daughter,
Ava, she made a big jump

00:15:18.340 --> 00:15:20.200
from figure skating to rugby.

00:15:20.200 --> 00:15:21.687
[LAUGHS] And so now--

00:15:21.687 --> 00:15:22.770
KATE T. PARKER: Obviously.

00:15:22.770 --> 00:15:25.510
ANDREW FERENCE: Now, she's
right into rugby and loving it.

00:15:25.510 --> 00:15:29.080
And you know, I
lean on rugby a lot.

00:15:29.080 --> 00:15:29.580
I love it.

00:15:29.580 --> 00:15:32.350
I played it growing up a bit.

00:15:32.350 --> 00:15:36.250
But the atmosphere--
there's a position

00:15:36.250 --> 00:15:40.410
for every type of
athlete on a rugby team.

00:15:40.410 --> 00:15:42.835
The first practice
that she went to, there

00:15:42.835 --> 00:15:45.220
was different teams
scattered all over the field,

00:15:45.220 --> 00:15:48.089
like different age groups,
different sex, everything.

00:15:48.089 --> 00:15:49.630
But at the end of
practice, everybody

00:15:49.630 --> 00:15:52.270
got together for a big
barbecue and had a big social.

00:15:52.270 --> 00:15:54.940
And so you're part of a family.

00:15:54.940 --> 00:15:58.690
So I saw a lot of
similarities with hockey.

00:15:58.690 --> 00:16:01.000
You know, it's a
smaller niche sport,

00:16:01.000 --> 00:16:02.960
but it has that kind
of family atmosphere

00:16:02.960 --> 00:16:06.976
and that real strong team bond.

00:16:06.976 --> 00:16:09.760
She's good at the sport,
but that atmosphere

00:16:09.760 --> 00:16:11.590
is what really dug into her.

00:16:11.590 --> 00:16:15.940
And she's part of a
bigger community, I guess.

00:16:15.940 --> 00:16:19.780
So to me, I think that
sports like that, that really

00:16:19.780 --> 00:16:22.600
encourage all different
types of athletes

00:16:22.600 --> 00:16:24.564
and different types
of body types,

00:16:24.564 --> 00:16:26.230
and you bring all
these people together,

00:16:26.230 --> 00:16:32.230
and you really purposely create
a community and a good feeling

00:16:32.230 --> 00:16:35.770
when you leave the
game or the practice,

00:16:35.770 --> 00:16:39.530
that's so important, because
that's what keeps kids there.

00:16:39.530 --> 00:16:41.410
You know, it's not
winning the medals

00:16:41.410 --> 00:16:43.870
and standing on the podium.

00:16:43.870 --> 00:16:46.300
That's a quick hit,
and that feels good.

00:16:46.300 --> 00:16:48.850
But that atmosphere
of family and feeling

00:16:48.850 --> 00:16:50.860
like you're part of
the big group, that

00:16:50.860 --> 00:16:53.830
keeps you in love with
the sport for life

00:16:53.830 --> 00:16:55.780
and active in the sport.

00:16:55.780 --> 00:16:57.867
SPEAKER 1: So this
is for both of you,

00:16:57.867 --> 00:16:59.950
but Kate, you kind of
mentioned that there was not

00:16:59.950 --> 00:17:02.710
a girls soccer team growing up.

00:17:02.710 --> 00:17:06.369
And then rugby is, historically,
a predominantly male sport.

00:17:06.369 --> 00:17:10.150
So I think with the evolution
of technology and social media,

00:17:10.150 --> 00:17:12.250
how have you seen
sports that maybe

00:17:12.250 --> 00:17:16.685
were very gender-specific now
not being as gender-specific?

00:17:16.685 --> 00:17:19.060
Have you seen the evolution
with your kids from, I guess,

00:17:19.060 --> 00:17:20.950
when you were growing up?

00:17:20.950 --> 00:17:23.530
KATE T. PARKER: I mean,
my kids don't ever

00:17:23.530 --> 00:17:25.930
think they can't do anything.

00:17:25.930 --> 00:17:30.570
My older daughter played
in a flag football league,

00:17:30.570 --> 00:17:32.560
and they were the only
girls team in there.

00:17:32.560 --> 00:17:35.800
And it's actually
like the perfect age.

00:17:35.800 --> 00:17:38.055
I think they were
11, so like right

00:17:38.055 --> 00:17:39.430
when they were at
the point where

00:17:39.430 --> 00:17:40.870
they were taller than the boys.

00:17:40.870 --> 00:17:45.040
And they're 13 now, it
wouldn't work anymore.

00:17:45.040 --> 00:17:49.420
But they don't
really seem to feel

00:17:49.420 --> 00:17:56.740
like they're defined by,
if girls aren't allowed

00:17:56.740 --> 00:17:58.000
or whatever.

00:17:58.000 --> 00:18:00.520
I feel like they would
protest that, you know?

00:18:00.520 --> 00:18:04.420
They are strong enough to
know, no, this is unfair

00:18:04.420 --> 00:18:06.020
and to make a stand.

00:18:06.020 --> 00:18:09.751
And I think that they're
open to anything.

00:18:09.751 --> 00:18:11.500
And they're like, oh,
that looks like fun.

00:18:11.500 --> 00:18:13.360
I want to do that.

00:18:13.360 --> 00:18:16.070
Of course, I can do
that, which is great.

00:18:16.070 --> 00:18:17.972
ANDREW FERENCE:
Yeah, I grew up--

00:18:17.972 --> 00:18:19.930
we had a girl on the
hockey team the whole time

00:18:19.930 --> 00:18:21.320
we grew up back in Canada.

00:18:21.320 --> 00:18:26.180
And so it wasn't really rare
to have a girl on your team.

00:18:26.180 --> 00:18:29.160
But looking back, it's
like there was one girl.

00:18:29.160 --> 00:18:31.540
And I imagine her
experience, being

00:18:31.540 --> 00:18:34.000
the only girl on the team,
must have been tough.

00:18:34.000 --> 00:18:36.910
Obviously now, the participation
levels of girls in hockey

00:18:36.910 --> 00:18:38.390
has shot way up.

00:18:38.390 --> 00:18:41.380
And that's attributed to great
work by the hockey associations

00:18:41.380 --> 00:18:44.490
to deliberately promote
it to girls, as well.

00:18:44.490 --> 00:18:46.240
And I think that's
probably the evolution,

00:18:46.240 --> 00:18:49.960
is the governing bodies,
places like the NHL,

00:18:49.960 --> 00:18:52.240
like deliberately
entering into that space

00:18:52.240 --> 00:18:56.950
to provide appropriate
programming for girls

00:18:56.950 --> 00:19:00.250
and to have proper
coaching curriculum

00:19:00.250 --> 00:19:02.560
and guidebooks on
how to make sure

00:19:02.560 --> 00:19:06.410
that this is a good space
for girls to come into

00:19:06.410 --> 00:19:08.610
and a good sport where
they feel welcome.

00:19:08.610 --> 00:19:10.360
Because you can't just
transfer everything

00:19:10.360 --> 00:19:12.310
that you do,
sometimes, and coach

00:19:12.310 --> 00:19:15.460
the same way, and everything
down to the locker rooms

00:19:15.460 --> 00:19:16.240
that are provided.

00:19:16.240 --> 00:19:18.073
There's a lot that goes
into it to make sure

00:19:18.073 --> 00:19:20.530
that, if a girl
chooses to play hockey,

00:19:20.530 --> 00:19:23.440
that she feels like she's
welcome, she's there.

00:19:23.440 --> 00:19:25.700
And so I think that's
probably the biggest change,

00:19:25.700 --> 00:19:28.750
is those deliberate
actions taken

00:19:28.750 --> 00:19:31.030
by things like USA
Hockey or the NHL

00:19:31.030 --> 00:19:36.310
to make sure that this is
a massive priority for us

00:19:36.310 --> 00:19:38.080
is to get it right
and to do it right.

00:19:38.080 --> 00:19:43.750
And I think that's the big
shift is the focus that's

00:19:43.750 --> 00:19:46.180
deliberately being put on it.

00:19:46.180 --> 00:19:49.780
SPEAKER 1: One kind of somewhat
sensitive, controversial topic

00:19:49.780 --> 00:19:52.690
that comes up a lot with
kids in sports these days is

00:19:52.690 --> 00:19:54.070
participation trophies.

00:19:54.070 --> 00:19:56.840
Do either of you have
strong opinions on that

00:19:56.840 --> 00:19:58.510
that you're willing to share?

00:19:58.510 --> 00:20:00.010
KATE T. PARKER:
I've kind of thought

00:20:00.010 --> 00:20:04.080
about this a little
bit, and I think

00:20:04.080 --> 00:20:08.670
the kids don't even buy them.

00:20:08.670 --> 00:20:12.450
If they know everybody gets
it just for being a part,

00:20:12.450 --> 00:20:14.810
then it doesn't mean anything.

00:20:14.810 --> 00:20:17.080
And I'm not against
making kids feel good,

00:20:17.080 --> 00:20:18.900
but if they're smart
enough to recognize

00:20:18.900 --> 00:20:22.620
that it's like
getting a T-shirt,

00:20:22.620 --> 00:20:27.660
I don't know that it's doing
what you set out to do.

00:20:31.200 --> 00:20:34.020
They should be sort
of the top, you know?

00:20:34.020 --> 00:20:36.300
If you get a trophy,
it means that you won,

00:20:36.300 --> 00:20:39.080
or you were the MVP.

00:20:39.080 --> 00:20:42.750
So yeah, my kids have definitely
gotten them over the years.

00:20:42.750 --> 00:20:46.260
But the ones that they have
earned and that they won

00:20:46.260 --> 00:20:49.240
are the ones that are
sitting out in their rooms.

00:20:49.240 --> 00:20:52.800
So I don't know that you're
not fooling any of the kids.

00:20:52.800 --> 00:20:54.265
You know?

00:20:54.265 --> 00:20:55.890
ANDREW FERENCE: When
I was a kid, yeah,

00:20:55.890 --> 00:21:00.610
I never would have wanted
the participation ribbon,

00:21:00.610 --> 00:21:01.110
or whatever.

00:21:01.110 --> 00:21:04.590
But growing up and becoming
older, and in the job

00:21:04.590 --> 00:21:07.500
that I'm in now,
I've been able to be

00:21:07.500 --> 00:21:09.510
part of good
presentations by, let's

00:21:09.510 --> 00:21:12.180
say, the country of Norway,
who doesn't keep score

00:21:12.180 --> 00:21:14.490
in their youth sports
system up until, I think,

00:21:14.490 --> 00:21:16.440
the age of 11 or 12.

00:21:16.440 --> 00:21:18.600
They're not allowed to
put any sports scores

00:21:18.600 --> 00:21:21.270
from youth sports in
newspapers, or print,

00:21:21.270 --> 00:21:23.520
or anything like that,
up until the age of 14.

00:21:23.520 --> 00:21:26.250
And so they create a real
culture of not keeping score.

00:21:26.250 --> 00:21:30.270
Everybody's playing, you know,
that equality in just keeping

00:21:30.270 --> 00:21:32.850
kids in a fun environment.

00:21:32.850 --> 00:21:35.010
And they've had
incredible success.

00:21:35.010 --> 00:21:40.290
Their gold medals per
ratio of population

00:21:40.290 --> 00:21:42.840
are absolutely insane
in these sports.

00:21:42.840 --> 00:21:46.080
And so there is some merit
to what they're doing

00:21:46.080 --> 00:21:49.410
and to the approach that they're
taking not only for their youth

00:21:49.410 --> 00:21:52.740
sport participation levels,
which are much higher than most

00:21:52.740 --> 00:21:55.030
of ours, they're
keeping kids in sport,

00:21:55.030 --> 00:21:59.230
but also producing
extremely elite athletes.

00:21:59.230 --> 00:22:02.270
So that's really swayed
me, is the results

00:22:02.270 --> 00:22:07.710
that countries have enacted
these kind of rules.

00:22:07.710 --> 00:22:10.230
And it's really producing.

00:22:10.230 --> 00:22:15.450
And from our perspective,
even at a league level,

00:22:15.450 --> 00:22:19.050
our main focus is not to make
the next batch of NHL hockey

00:22:19.050 --> 00:22:20.250
players.

00:22:20.250 --> 00:22:23.970
Our focus is to make sure that
people come away from a hockey

00:22:23.970 --> 00:22:26.189
rink and have a good
experience, because we

00:22:26.189 --> 00:22:27.480
want them to stay in the sport.

00:22:27.480 --> 00:22:31.015
And when you ask kids,
why did you come back

00:22:31.015 --> 00:22:31.890
the following season?

00:22:31.890 --> 00:22:33.550
They're like, oh, it was fun.

00:22:33.550 --> 00:22:35.610
So to us, that means
our number one priority

00:22:35.610 --> 00:22:38.550
is to make sure that
the sport is fun.

00:22:38.550 --> 00:22:42.000
If that means going the route
of not necessarily keeping

00:22:42.000 --> 00:22:43.410
score, making it--

00:22:43.410 --> 00:22:47.250
so our governing
bodies have done a lot.

00:22:47.250 --> 00:22:50.580
They've shrunk down the
size of a hockey rink,

00:22:50.580 --> 00:22:53.010
and they play a different
form of hockey in a smaller

00:22:53.010 --> 00:22:55.380
space for little kids because
it's more fun to actually

00:22:55.380 --> 00:22:58.710
be involved in the game, rather
than just watching the good kid

00:22:58.710 --> 00:23:01.560
steal the puck and skate off.

00:23:01.560 --> 00:23:05.670
So there are actual
changes in our games

00:23:05.670 --> 00:23:09.360
that we've made at a higher
level to produce more fun.

00:23:09.360 --> 00:23:12.055
And I think that's basically
what it falls down to, for us.

00:23:12.055 --> 00:23:13.430
SPEAKER 1: So
Andrew, earlier you

00:23:13.430 --> 00:23:16.739
talked, when we spoke before,
about teaching your daughters

00:23:16.739 --> 00:23:18.780
about who they are versus
who they want to become

00:23:18.780 --> 00:23:19.990
and who they want to be.

00:23:19.990 --> 00:23:23.340
Can you talk a little bit about
how that mentality has played

00:23:23.340 --> 00:23:26.050
a role in your parenting?

00:23:26.050 --> 00:23:29.040
ANDREW FERENCE:
Well, I want them

00:23:29.040 --> 00:23:32.370
to, obviously, like I
said, shoot for the stars

00:23:32.370 --> 00:23:35.430
and, if they have a
dream of doing something,

00:23:35.430 --> 00:23:37.177
know that they can do it.

00:23:37.177 --> 00:23:38.510
Like, the world is their oyster.

00:23:38.510 --> 00:23:40.240
They're obviously
extremely privileged.

00:23:40.240 --> 00:23:41.690
They have great,
great schooling.

00:23:41.690 --> 00:23:45.270
They have every
opportunity in the world,

00:23:45.270 --> 00:23:48.690
but they have to use it and
not waste that opportunity.

00:23:48.690 --> 00:23:52.050
And so I think giving
them every option,

00:23:52.050 --> 00:23:54.489
exposing them to as
many things as possible

00:23:54.489 --> 00:23:56.280
and making sure that
they know that they're

00:23:56.280 --> 00:24:00.192
capable to try
something new and do it,

00:24:00.192 --> 00:24:01.650
that's probably
the conversation we

00:24:01.650 --> 00:24:06.426
have the most when we have
our deep dad-daughter talks.

00:24:06.426 --> 00:24:07.800
Like, why are we
doing something?

00:24:07.800 --> 00:24:10.710
Or what is our philosophy?

00:24:10.710 --> 00:24:12.780
It really is, as
I said, what I am

00:24:12.780 --> 00:24:17.160
trying to give you the ability
to do is, when you're older

00:24:17.160 --> 00:24:19.710
and you have a group of friends,
or you have some co-workers,

00:24:19.710 --> 00:24:23.310
you have a new boy that you
like or girl that you like,

00:24:23.310 --> 00:24:26.312
or whatever it is, and they
say, hey, let's go do this,

00:24:26.312 --> 00:24:28.770
you can say, yep, let's do it,
even if you've never done it

00:24:28.770 --> 00:24:32.010
before, because you have the
confidence and the capabilities

00:24:32.010 --> 00:24:33.930
to try new things.

00:24:33.930 --> 00:24:36.720
I've ran into a
lot of people, even

00:24:36.720 --> 00:24:38.460
at a professional
sports level, that

00:24:38.460 --> 00:24:42.150
were afraid to go play a game
of tennis because they're like,

00:24:42.150 --> 00:24:43.690
oh, I've never played tennis.

00:24:43.690 --> 00:24:45.384
And these are
professional NHL players,

00:24:45.384 --> 00:24:46.800
like, I don't want
to play tennis.

00:24:46.800 --> 00:24:48.000
I've never played that before.

00:24:48.000 --> 00:24:49.416
But what it was
is because they're

00:24:49.416 --> 00:24:51.370
scared to not be
good at something,

00:24:51.370 --> 00:24:54.330
or they had that lack
of self-confidence

00:24:54.330 --> 00:24:56.730
to try something
new and understand

00:24:56.730 --> 00:25:00.220
that it's all right to
not be great at something.

00:25:00.220 --> 00:25:02.530
And so I guess
that's really what

00:25:02.530 --> 00:25:04.130
I want to give them
the ability to,

00:25:04.130 --> 00:25:05.850
is to try as many
things as possible,

00:25:05.850 --> 00:25:10.340
to jump into scary situations,
to try something wild once

00:25:10.340 --> 00:25:14.240
in a while and not be afraid
of being a little bit afraid.

00:25:14.240 --> 00:25:17.650
So I guess, yeah, that's a
long-winded answer to it.

00:25:17.650 --> 00:25:18.650
SPEAKER 1: That's great.

00:25:18.650 --> 00:25:20.480
I want to go back--

00:25:20.480 --> 00:25:23.120
maybe there too-- to
Kate, to your photos.

00:25:23.120 --> 00:25:24.165
KATE T. PARKER: Yeah.

00:25:24.165 --> 00:25:26.540
SPEAKER 1: And this is, I
believe, a year or two old now,

00:25:26.540 --> 00:25:28.164
but why do you think
these photos still

00:25:28.164 --> 00:25:30.130
resonate so much today?

00:25:30.130 --> 00:25:32.540
KATE T. PARKER:
Well, sadly, I think

00:25:32.540 --> 00:25:37.640
it's rare to see-- like
on social media, most

00:25:37.640 --> 00:25:40.970
everything we see is
filtered, or face-tuned,

00:25:40.970 --> 00:25:50.420
or set up to show an unrealistic
depiction of women or girls.

00:25:50.420 --> 00:25:55.280
And I feel like this
shows who these girls are.

00:25:55.280 --> 00:25:58.202
It shows a rawness
and a realness

00:25:58.202 --> 00:26:00.080
to what girls are interested in.

00:26:00.080 --> 00:26:02.040
Like, they're screaming.

00:26:02.040 --> 00:26:03.050
They're sweating.

00:26:03.050 --> 00:26:04.310
They're playing baseball.

00:26:04.310 --> 00:26:10.490
They're enjoying when they
clean the fire hydrants.

00:26:10.490 --> 00:26:15.290
And yeah, I think
that people see these,

00:26:15.290 --> 00:26:19.880
and it either reminds them
of who they used to be,

00:26:19.880 --> 00:26:23.390
or reminds them of who
their kids are now,

00:26:23.390 --> 00:26:25.520
as parents and stuff.

00:26:25.520 --> 00:26:29.450
Like this picture in the middle
of Alice, that's my daughter,

00:26:29.450 --> 00:26:32.950
has gotten stolen so many times.

00:26:32.950 --> 00:26:35.390
And it's a meme.

00:26:35.390 --> 00:26:36.620
It says, remember her?

00:26:36.620 --> 00:26:39.950
Remember when you
used to be this girl?

00:26:39.950 --> 00:26:42.800
And I don't even mind anymore.

00:26:42.800 --> 00:26:46.550
I'm like, if this is encouraging
people to remember when they--

00:26:46.550 --> 00:26:49.640
because I feel like when
you're a kid, before you

00:26:49.640 --> 00:26:55.250
reach puberty, you have
this sense of I am awesome.

00:26:55.250 --> 00:26:57.150
I can do anything.

00:26:57.150 --> 00:27:00.110
And then it just kind of
gets-- not beaten out of you,

00:27:00.110 --> 00:27:01.930
but you just lose it.

00:27:01.930 --> 00:27:05.330
And if these remind
people of when

00:27:05.330 --> 00:27:07.280
they had a sense of
possibility and when

00:27:07.280 --> 00:27:11.330
they had a sense that they
were such badasses, that if it

00:27:11.330 --> 00:27:12.830
can remind people of that--

00:27:12.830 --> 00:27:16.005
I think that's why people
respond to it because that's

00:27:16.005 --> 00:27:16.880
what these girls are.

00:27:16.880 --> 00:27:19.640
Because when I shoot girls,
when I shoot them for the book,

00:27:19.640 --> 00:27:22.070
I'm generally shooting
them doing the thing

00:27:22.070 --> 00:27:26.780
that they love the most, the
thing that is their passion.

00:27:26.780 --> 00:27:29.160
And they are confident, and
I think it comes through.

00:27:29.160 --> 00:27:33.380
So people want to see
that, because I think we

00:27:33.380 --> 00:27:34.829
all need more of that.

00:27:34.829 --> 00:27:36.620
SPEAKER 1: And that's
a good transition to,

00:27:36.620 --> 00:27:37.989
what are you working on next?

00:27:37.989 --> 00:27:38.780
KATE T. PARKER: OK.

00:27:38.780 --> 00:27:40.370
SPEAKER 1: We have the cover.

00:27:40.370 --> 00:27:41.245
KATE T. PARKER: Yeah.

00:27:41.245 --> 00:27:43.590
So this is my nephew.

00:27:43.590 --> 00:27:47.270
And so the other cover
is my other daughter.

00:27:47.270 --> 00:27:50.270
So Alice, my
daughter, is not happy

00:27:50.270 --> 00:27:52.020
that she's not on the
cover of a book yet.

00:27:52.020 --> 00:27:53.880
[LAUGHTER]

00:27:53.880 --> 00:27:55.620
We're working on it, Al.

00:27:55.620 --> 00:27:57.620
So this is my nephew,
AND this book is called,

00:27:57.620 --> 00:27:59.540
"The Heart of a Boy."

00:27:59.540 --> 00:28:04.010
And it was funny,
because I was asked

00:28:04.010 --> 00:28:06.920
to consider doing
a book about boys,

00:28:06.920 --> 00:28:10.250
and I was very reluctant
because I was like,

00:28:10.250 --> 00:28:13.280
no, boy's voices are heard.

00:28:13.280 --> 00:28:15.470
I need to talk about our girls.

00:28:15.470 --> 00:28:17.270
You know, that's
what my focus was.

00:28:17.270 --> 00:28:18.960
I literally was crying about it.

00:28:18.960 --> 00:28:21.084
And then I was like, you
know, I told my publisher,

00:28:21.084 --> 00:28:21.860
I said, I'll try.

00:28:21.860 --> 00:28:24.210
I'll try to shoot a little bit.

00:28:24.210 --> 00:28:26.840
And I shot just a few
sessions with boys

00:28:26.840 --> 00:28:28.040
that were local to me.

00:28:28.040 --> 00:28:33.980
And immediately, I realized that
the vulnerability and the depth

00:28:33.980 --> 00:28:36.200
of feeling that these
boys had was something

00:28:36.200 --> 00:28:40.250
that I wasn't aware of,
something that I didn't

00:28:40.250 --> 00:28:42.920
realize needed to be heard.

00:28:42.920 --> 00:28:45.800
And throughout the tour for
"Strong is the New Pretty",

00:28:45.800 --> 00:28:48.980
and every time I would
speak, little boys

00:28:48.980 --> 00:28:50.245
would say, where's my book?

00:28:50.245 --> 00:28:52.370
Miss Kate, are you going
to do the book about boys?

00:28:52.370 --> 00:28:54.740
And I was like, y'all
don't need a book at all.

00:28:54.740 --> 00:28:55.820
You're fine.

00:28:55.820 --> 00:29:00.050
And then I was like--

00:29:00.050 --> 00:29:01.460
I was unaware of this.

00:29:01.460 --> 00:29:03.170
And through the
shooting of it, I

00:29:03.170 --> 00:29:05.900
realized that-- so the
definition, and even in 2018,

00:29:05.900 --> 00:29:08.510
for girls is fairly
narrow of what they can be

00:29:08.510 --> 00:29:09.870
and what they can do.

00:29:09.870 --> 00:29:12.650
But I feel like there's
so much that's helping

00:29:12.650 --> 00:29:15.050
to broaden that and so many
opportunities for girls

00:29:15.050 --> 00:29:16.010
to be who they want.

00:29:16.010 --> 00:29:19.590
And there's books, and
clothing, and TV shows.

00:29:19.590 --> 00:29:23.930
But for boys in 2018, the
definition is even more narrow.

00:29:23.930 --> 00:29:27.410
So if you step out of
that athlete-leader,

00:29:27.410 --> 00:29:28.580
you're kind of lost.

00:29:28.580 --> 00:29:33.140
And so I wanted to take that
same message of acceptance

00:29:33.140 --> 00:29:36.200
of self and celebration of
self and extend it to boys.

00:29:36.200 --> 00:29:38.420
So with "Strong is
the New Pretty,"

00:29:38.420 --> 00:29:43.790
the focus was on more
about toughness and grit.

00:29:43.790 --> 00:29:46.550
And for "Heart of a Boy,"
I focused a little bit more

00:29:46.550 --> 00:29:50.360
on the sensitivity,
and vulnerability,

00:29:50.360 --> 00:29:51.920
and including everything.

00:29:51.920 --> 00:29:54.710
But I just wanted those
boys' voices to be heard.

00:29:54.710 --> 00:29:56.540
And I really, really enjoyed it.

00:29:56.540 --> 00:29:58.970
And I'm so excited
for it to come out.

00:29:58.970 --> 00:30:00.390
It comes out in April.

00:30:00.390 --> 00:30:01.640
SPEAKER 1: Exciting.

00:30:01.640 --> 00:30:03.025
And Andrew, you
work for the NHL?

00:30:03.025 --> 00:30:03.900
ANDREW FERENCE: Yeah.

00:30:03.900 --> 00:30:05.691
SPEAKER 1: What are
you working on in terms

00:30:05.691 --> 00:30:07.110
of the social impact?

00:30:07.110 --> 00:30:10.800
ANDREW FERENCE: We have
a great team at the NHL.

00:30:10.800 --> 00:30:12.540
It's a new department.

00:30:12.540 --> 00:30:16.344
My boss, Kim Davis, was
brought in in January

00:30:16.344 --> 00:30:17.760
from completely
outside of hockey.

00:30:17.760 --> 00:30:20.550
And she's been just a dynamo.

00:30:20.550 --> 00:30:24.390
She's put together a team
of people here in New York

00:30:24.390 --> 00:30:25.740
and in Toronto.

00:30:25.740 --> 00:30:28.470
We do social impact,
legislative affairs,

00:30:28.470 --> 00:30:31.860
and we help to look for growth
initiatives in the game.

00:30:31.860 --> 00:30:36.360
So I get to spread myself
out across those three.

00:30:36.360 --> 00:30:38.550
Probably right now,
the most I'm doing

00:30:38.550 --> 00:30:40.740
is in legislative affairs,
especially up in Canada,

00:30:40.740 --> 00:30:42.210
in Ottawa.

00:30:42.210 --> 00:30:45.450
And I get to take the passion
for getting kids involved

00:30:45.450 --> 00:30:50.400
in sport and have more access to
sport specifically to females,

00:30:50.400 --> 00:30:53.280
just because the participation
numbers are lower.

00:30:53.280 --> 00:30:55.110
And in Canada, I get
the distinct advantage

00:30:55.110 --> 00:30:57.970
because our health care
system is universal.

00:30:57.970 --> 00:31:01.050
So I can really go in
there with good hard data.

00:31:01.050 --> 00:31:03.510
We have good partnerships
through the Aspen Institute

00:31:03.510 --> 00:31:06.660
with John Hopkins and
some different groups

00:31:06.660 --> 00:31:14.610
that have some unbelievable data
on the cost of non-active kids.

00:31:14.610 --> 00:31:16.710
How much that costs us,
society-wise, as far

00:31:16.710 --> 00:31:20.260
as health care costs,
is astronomical.

00:31:20.260 --> 00:31:23.220
So a lot of the work is going in
and having these conversations

00:31:23.220 --> 00:31:25.860
with government
officials, looking

00:31:25.860 --> 00:31:29.100
for more access to sport,
everything from infrastructure

00:31:29.100 --> 00:31:31.890
funding to programming,
and really tying it

00:31:31.890 --> 00:31:34.200
to the importance of
the investment in having

00:31:34.200 --> 00:31:35.670
kids play sport--

00:31:35.670 --> 00:31:38.700
physical health, mental health,
the grades you get at school,

00:31:38.700 --> 00:31:40.800
staying out of the
justice system.

00:31:40.800 --> 00:31:43.740
I think sport truly is--
it's not just a passion,

00:31:43.740 --> 00:31:46.260
and it's not just about
winning medals at the Olympics,

00:31:46.260 --> 00:31:48.750
but it really is an
incredibly important part

00:31:48.750 --> 00:31:52.110
of the health of our countries.

00:31:52.110 --> 00:31:54.420
So yeah, going strong
with those messages

00:31:54.420 --> 00:31:58.210
and, thankfully, have
very receptive ears.

00:31:58.210 --> 00:32:02.160
And I think that there's a lot
of really, really good people,

00:32:02.160 --> 00:32:04.770
both in not just our
league at the NHL,

00:32:04.770 --> 00:32:06.810
but across all of the
professional leagues--

00:32:06.810 --> 00:32:08.350
we have a lot of crossover--

00:32:08.350 --> 00:32:10.170
and then at a government level.

00:32:10.170 --> 00:32:12.065
It's just a matter
of getting it right,

00:32:12.065 --> 00:32:14.730
and making sure that the funding
is going where it needs to be,

00:32:14.730 --> 00:32:16.980
and that we're really accessing
the kids that need it.

00:32:19.197 --> 00:32:21.030
There's a lot of kids
that play every sport,

00:32:21.030 --> 00:32:22.470
like I did growing up.

00:32:22.470 --> 00:32:24.150
But unfortunately,
there's a ton of kids

00:32:24.150 --> 00:32:26.410
that have access to no sport.

00:32:26.410 --> 00:32:28.620
And so that's really
what we're trying to do

00:32:28.620 --> 00:32:30.616
is making sure that
we don't have tons

00:32:30.616 --> 00:32:31.865
of kids falling in the cracks.

00:32:31.865 --> 00:32:34.470
And we want those
kids playing hockey

00:32:34.470 --> 00:32:35.834
and being introduced our sport.

00:32:35.834 --> 00:32:37.500
We really see our
sport not only as good

00:32:37.500 --> 00:32:40.740
for being active and
whatnot, but to that point

00:32:40.740 --> 00:32:42.990
of feeling like you're
part of a better community.

00:32:42.990 --> 00:32:45.750
And through our
curriculum and coaching,

00:32:45.750 --> 00:32:47.400
we're really pushing
those messages

00:32:47.400 --> 00:32:52.860
of confidence, teamwork,
humility, a family setting.

00:32:52.860 --> 00:32:55.350
Those are all extremely
important to us.

00:32:55.350 --> 00:32:57.240
Like I said, creating
the next NHLers

00:32:57.240 --> 00:32:58.950
is not a priority at all.

00:32:58.950 --> 00:33:00.780
So I have a lot of fun at work.

00:33:00.780 --> 00:33:02.390
I've got great
people to work with.

00:33:02.390 --> 00:33:04.410
SPEAKER 1: And it's a little bit
of the Hockey is for Everyone?

00:33:04.410 --> 00:33:05.940
ANDREW FERENCE: Hockey is
for Everyone, you know?

00:33:05.940 --> 00:33:08.900
And we're really trying to not
just have that as a tagline,

00:33:08.900 --> 00:33:11.610
but live it.

00:33:11.610 --> 00:33:13.050
And we have a lot of work to do.

00:33:13.050 --> 00:33:15.544
Hockey is, like I said,
it's a bit of a niche sport.

00:33:15.544 --> 00:33:16.335
It's very regional.

00:33:19.020 --> 00:33:22.530
If you looked at us compared to
the demographics in the States,

00:33:22.530 --> 00:33:23.770
they don't line up.

00:33:23.770 --> 00:33:25.170
And so that is a
big push for us.

00:33:25.170 --> 00:33:27.850
We have markets
across North America.

00:33:27.850 --> 00:33:30.270
And we need to have the
people playing our sport

00:33:30.270 --> 00:33:31.840
look like our markets.

00:33:31.840 --> 00:33:32.340
Yeah.

00:33:32.340 --> 00:33:35.320
So that's a big job, but
it's important to us.

