00:34:34.751 --> 00:34:36.250
I was playing for
Boston, obviously,

00:34:36.250 --> 00:34:39.630
and this game was in
Montreal, in the playoffs.

00:34:39.630 --> 00:34:41.540
For those that don't
know, Boston-Montreal

00:34:41.540 --> 00:34:44.670
is the ultimate
rivalry in hockey.

00:34:44.670 --> 00:34:46.090
This was years into the rivalry.

00:34:46.090 --> 00:34:47.610
We had faced off
against each other.

00:34:47.610 --> 00:34:49.712
And it's for real.

00:34:49.712 --> 00:34:51.420
We'd go up to Montreal
and play up there,

00:34:51.420 --> 00:34:54.510
and they'd be outside of
our hotel at 3 o'clock

00:34:54.510 --> 00:34:56.500
in the morning,
pulling the semi horns,

00:34:56.500 --> 00:35:00.390
like, wha, wha, pulling the
fire alarm, rocking our bus,

00:35:00.390 --> 00:35:02.440
like all kinds of crazy stuff.

00:35:02.440 --> 00:35:05.251
And then the Boston fans would
be just as friendly to them,

00:35:05.251 --> 00:35:06.750
probably, when they
came down to us.

00:35:06.750 --> 00:35:09.330
And so this rivalry
was for real.

00:35:09.330 --> 00:35:12.400
So anyways, in this
game, we're down--

00:35:12.400 --> 00:35:14.400
down in the game,
down in the series.

00:35:14.400 --> 00:35:16.950
And I got kind of a lucky
bounce and scored a goal.

00:35:16.950 --> 00:35:20.820
And this is just like
pure, raw, stupid emotion.

00:35:20.820 --> 00:35:23.460
And not until after
the game, it was like,

00:35:23.460 --> 00:35:25.015
oh, that was really dumb.

00:35:25.015 --> 00:35:26.890
KATE T. PARKER: So this
was your celebration?

00:35:26.890 --> 00:35:27.495
ANDREW FERENCE: This
was my celebration.

00:35:27.495 --> 00:35:27.995
[LAUGHTER]

00:35:27.995 --> 00:35:29.730
SPEAKER 1: [INAUDIBLE]
celebration.

00:35:29.730 --> 00:35:32.010
ANDREW FERENCE: In Montreal.

00:35:32.010 --> 00:35:33.840
And it was a really
dumb thing to do,

00:35:33.840 --> 00:35:35.326
because obviously,
you don't want

00:35:35.326 --> 00:35:37.200
to get suspended in the
playoffs and whatnot.

00:35:37.200 --> 00:35:38.548
And so I just was like--

00:35:38.548 --> 00:35:39.339
I didn't even know.

00:35:39.339 --> 00:35:42.300
I've got to figure a way
out of this situation.

00:35:42.300 --> 00:35:44.850
I explained it to my
kids like, sometimes, you

00:35:44.850 --> 00:35:48.518
do a lot of stupid things
in the quest for victory,

00:35:48.518 --> 00:35:50.142
and this is one of
those stupid things.

00:35:50.142 --> 00:35:52.712
So I made up an excuse that--

00:35:52.712 --> 00:35:54.420
you know, I didn't
want to get suspended,

00:35:54.420 --> 00:35:56.400
so I said, well, I was
just giving a fist pump.

00:35:56.400 --> 00:35:59.280
And I was wearing brand new
gloves, and they got stuck.

00:35:59.280 --> 00:36:01.260
And I'm like, I'm really sorry.

00:36:01.260 --> 00:36:03.514
They're just stiff.

00:36:03.514 --> 00:36:05.055
KATE T. PARKER: Just
that one finger.

00:36:05.055 --> 00:36:06.990
[LAUGHS]

00:36:06.990 --> 00:36:09.240
ANDREW FERENCE: The league
official on the other line,

00:36:09.240 --> 00:36:12.360
you could tell, he
was just like, really?

00:36:12.360 --> 00:36:13.680
So I got fined.

00:36:13.680 --> 00:36:16.410
I took a pretty good
fine for that one.

00:36:16.410 --> 00:36:17.700
And I feel really bad.

00:36:17.700 --> 00:36:19.530
I feel more stupid
about lying about it.

00:36:19.530 --> 00:36:24.600
I should have just owned it,
but there's some humor to it.

00:36:24.600 --> 00:36:26.730
I get a lot of Montreal
fans that actually give it

00:36:26.730 --> 00:36:27.996
right back to me, so yeah.

00:36:27.996 --> 00:36:28.830
[LAUGHS]

00:36:28.830 --> 00:36:30.330
But the funniest
part of the story

00:36:30.330 --> 00:36:32.310
is actually going
back to Boston.

00:36:32.310 --> 00:36:35.820
And Boston fans are literally
the best sports fans,

00:36:35.820 --> 00:36:38.080
bar none in the entire world.

00:36:38.080 --> 00:36:39.240
And I end up back.

00:36:39.240 --> 00:36:43.290
And I live in the North End
in the Italian area of Boston.

00:36:43.290 --> 00:36:45.884
And I show up to my condo, and
on the buzzer board-- you know,

00:36:45.884 --> 00:36:48.300
when you buzz in to get into
your building-- so I walk up,

00:36:48.300 --> 00:36:51.420
and there's all these envelopes
taped to the buzzer board.

00:36:51.420 --> 00:36:52.530
And I'm looking at them.

00:36:52.530 --> 00:36:55.350
Open up, and there's
notes, like, go Bruins!

00:36:55.350 --> 00:36:56.070
Whatever.

00:36:56.070 --> 00:36:57.960
And they're full of money.

00:36:57.960 --> 00:37:00.405
So people knew that I had
been fined for doing this.

00:37:00.405 --> 00:37:01.530
KATE T. PARKER: Oh, my god.

00:37:01.530 --> 00:37:03.821
ANDREW FERENCE: And so the
neighborhood was taping up--

00:37:03.821 --> 00:37:04.631
KATE T. PARKER: Oh.

00:37:04.631 --> 00:37:06.880
ANDREW FERENCE: So they paid
off some of it, at least.

00:37:06.880 --> 00:37:07.380
[LAUGHTER]

00:37:07.380 --> 00:37:10.140
And we ended up winning
the Cup that year.

00:37:10.140 --> 00:37:16.470
So the North End lore is that
this is what turned the tide

00:37:16.470 --> 00:37:18.820
and got us the Cup, right?

00:37:18.820 --> 00:37:20.910
But it's, yeah, infamous,
to say the least.

00:37:20.910 --> 00:37:22.035
KATE T. PARKER: It's funny.

00:37:22.035 --> 00:37:25.560
SPEAKER 1: Is there
anybody that has questions?

00:37:25.560 --> 00:37:27.208
I'll get this off
the screen for you.

00:37:27.208 --> 00:37:28.840
ANDREW FERENCE: Yeah.

00:37:28.840 --> 00:37:29.340
Yeah.

00:37:29.340 --> 00:37:30.710
I have artwork at home.

00:37:30.710 --> 00:37:32.970
And this guy made this big--

00:37:32.970 --> 00:37:37.620
not collage, but kind of like
a really nice portrait of that.

00:37:37.620 --> 00:37:38.471
And I was like, oh.

00:37:38.471 --> 00:37:38.971
[LAUGHTER]

00:37:38.971 --> 00:37:39.764
Yeah.

00:37:39.764 --> 00:37:40.626
[INAUDIBLE]

00:37:40.626 --> 00:37:42.359
KATE T. PARKER: That's awesome.

00:37:42.359 --> 00:37:42.900
AUDIENCE: Hi.

00:37:42.900 --> 00:37:44.209
Thanks, so much for coming.

00:37:44.209 --> 00:37:45.000
My name is Carissa.

00:37:45.000 --> 00:37:47.460
I have two young girls.

00:37:47.460 --> 00:37:49.350
I have a question
more around, Kate,

00:37:49.350 --> 00:37:50.850
what you were talking
about, was how

00:37:50.850 --> 00:37:56.010
to inspire girls to think that
they can accomplish anything.

00:37:56.010 --> 00:37:59.200
I think I've seen,
actually, a lot

00:37:59.200 --> 00:38:00.900
of the opposite in
my daughter, who's

00:38:00.900 --> 00:38:04.240
turning five, very early on,
saying, this is for boys,

00:38:04.240 --> 00:38:07.140
and this is for girls, coming
from a lot of different areas.

00:38:07.140 --> 00:38:09.970
And I thought taking the
picture of your daughter

00:38:09.970 --> 00:38:13.830
and really showing her how
you see her through your eyes

00:38:13.830 --> 00:38:16.320
and the world can see you is
a really good example of how

00:38:16.320 --> 00:38:17.100
to inspire that.

00:38:17.100 --> 00:38:19.170
But can you talk
more about other ways

00:38:19.170 --> 00:38:22.584
to help girls see
themselves as being

00:38:22.584 --> 00:38:23.750
able to accomplish anything?

00:38:23.750 --> 00:38:24.060
KATE T. PARKER: Yeah.

00:38:24.060 --> 00:38:25.610
I mean, that's so young.

00:38:25.610 --> 00:38:26.130
And yeah.

00:38:26.130 --> 00:38:28.440
And I'm sure if
you're questioning it,

00:38:28.440 --> 00:38:31.420
you're not the one saying
to her, girls don't do that.

00:38:31.420 --> 00:38:33.410
And you're like, where
is this coming from?

00:38:33.410 --> 00:38:36.180
And I mean, I think one of
the things that you can do

00:38:36.180 --> 00:38:36.775
is just--

00:38:36.775 --> 00:38:38.400
I know five is young--
but you can just

00:38:38.400 --> 00:38:41.220
have those conversations
of, no, no, no, no,

00:38:41.220 --> 00:38:44.610
you can do anything and then
actually it going into practice

00:38:44.610 --> 00:38:45.780
and challenging her.

00:38:45.780 --> 00:38:51.319
And go to a climbing gym, or
whatever she's interested in.

00:38:51.319 --> 00:38:52.860
That's one of the
things that I think

00:38:52.860 --> 00:38:57.180
is so important for us, as
parents, is to parent the kids

00:38:57.180 --> 00:39:00.030
that we have, not who
we wish they were.

00:39:00.030 --> 00:39:02.040
So kind of let her self-direct.

00:39:02.040 --> 00:39:05.640
Whatever she likes to do,
be fully invested in it

00:39:05.640 --> 00:39:07.560
and take or do it.

00:39:07.560 --> 00:39:08.500
But yeah.

00:39:08.500 --> 00:39:10.900
And I feel like it's a constant.

00:39:10.900 --> 00:39:12.400
For me, it's a
constant conversation

00:39:12.400 --> 00:39:13.270
I have with my kids.

00:39:13.270 --> 00:39:15.340
I remember, I took
a picture of this.

00:39:15.340 --> 00:39:19.810
We walked into Target, or we
walked into a store, whatever

00:39:19.810 --> 00:39:23.440
the store is, and it
had like building sets,

00:39:23.440 --> 00:39:25.060
and then girls building sets.

00:39:25.060 --> 00:39:29.569
And I said to the girls, and
I was like, how dumb is that?

00:39:29.569 --> 00:39:31.360
And they're like, yeah,
that's really dumb.

00:39:31.360 --> 00:39:34.840
And I think it's just like a
constant, hey, do you see this?

00:39:34.840 --> 00:39:36.850
Why is this aisle pink?

00:39:36.850 --> 00:39:38.269
Girls don't always like pink.

00:39:38.269 --> 00:39:39.810
Do you want to go
to the other aisle?

00:39:39.810 --> 00:39:42.190
Let's go get something else.

00:39:42.190 --> 00:39:44.980
You're not always having
a big conversation.

00:39:44.980 --> 00:39:48.210
It's just little things that
you're always being like,

00:39:48.210 --> 00:39:49.210
no, let's question that.

00:39:49.210 --> 00:39:50.260
That's silly.

00:39:50.260 --> 00:39:52.537
Why is that?

00:39:52.537 --> 00:39:54.370
And it's just like
you're always going to be

00:39:54.370 --> 00:39:56.500
the mom questioning things.

00:39:56.500 --> 00:39:58.750
But then that's good, because
that's what she's doing.

00:39:58.750 --> 00:40:01.041
And I think it's probably
she's getting it from school,

00:40:01.041 --> 00:40:02.420
or TV shows, or whatever.

00:40:02.420 --> 00:40:04.610
So I think it's just, you
just have to be vigilant.

00:40:04.610 --> 00:40:07.690
And if you're wondering
about it, then

00:40:07.690 --> 00:40:09.290
then you're going to do it.

00:40:09.290 --> 00:40:13.432
And I think it's getting
books that teach other--

00:40:13.432 --> 00:40:14.890
and there's so much
stuff for girls

00:40:14.890 --> 00:40:19.810
to help them recognize
that there's not limits.

00:40:19.810 --> 00:40:21.820
It's just constantly
questioning gender roles.

00:40:21.820 --> 00:40:25.060
I have a journal, "Strong
is the New Pretty" journal.

00:40:25.060 --> 00:40:28.570
And one of the activities
in there is to go in a store

00:40:28.570 --> 00:40:32.355
and pick out three things
that are based on gender norms

00:40:32.355 --> 00:40:34.480
and write them down, just
to make kids aware of it.

00:40:34.480 --> 00:40:37.190
Because we don't even
recognize it, sometimes.

00:40:37.190 --> 00:40:39.040
So I think it's
just being aware,

00:40:39.040 --> 00:40:41.890
and then being like,
that's pretty dumb.

00:40:41.890 --> 00:40:42.570
But it's hard.

00:40:42.570 --> 00:40:44.170
That's so young.

00:40:44.170 --> 00:40:46.330
Good job, though, good
job for recognizing it.

00:40:49.590 --> 00:40:50.560
AUDIENCE: Hi.

00:40:50.560 --> 00:40:52.610
Thanks, for being here.

00:40:52.610 --> 00:40:56.500
My name is Melissa, I
am not a parent yet.

00:40:56.500 --> 00:40:57.780
I am an athlete.

00:40:57.780 --> 00:41:01.687
I'm a fitness coach, so
this is all really valuable

00:41:01.687 --> 00:41:02.520
for me to listen to.

00:41:02.520 --> 00:41:04.480
So as somebody who
isn't a parent,

00:41:04.480 --> 00:41:07.600
but really appreciates being
involved in the athlete

00:41:07.600 --> 00:41:09.700
community-- not necessarily
to your point, Andrew,

00:41:09.700 --> 00:41:11.560
of developing
professional athletes,

00:41:11.560 --> 00:41:15.790
but just getting women,
girls, involved in sport--

00:41:15.790 --> 00:41:17.530
I think, from
personal experience,

00:41:17.530 --> 00:41:18.905
we're living in
a space right now

00:41:18.905 --> 00:41:20.560
with all this
social media where,

00:41:20.560 --> 00:41:23.290
even as an amateur
athlete, or as somebody

00:41:23.290 --> 00:41:25.510
who is a local
fitness professional,

00:41:25.510 --> 00:41:30.250
we're looking at things where
you want to become somebody

00:41:30.250 --> 00:41:31.720
who helps inspire other people.

00:41:31.720 --> 00:41:33.220
And one of the ways
that you do that

00:41:33.220 --> 00:41:35.660
is becoming an
instructor, being a coach.

00:41:35.660 --> 00:41:37.660
And a lot of places that
employ people like that

00:41:37.660 --> 00:41:41.001
are asking for things like
your photography portfolio.

00:41:41.001 --> 00:41:43.000
They want to know what
modeling photos you have.

00:41:43.000 --> 00:41:44.666
They want to know how
many followers you

00:41:44.666 --> 00:41:45.830
have on your social media.

00:41:45.830 --> 00:41:48.340
And social media is a space
where conventional beauty

00:41:48.340 --> 00:41:50.650
is still very highly ranked.

00:41:50.650 --> 00:41:52.600
So again, as somebody
who's not a parent,

00:41:52.600 --> 00:41:55.150
but wants to support
young women developing

00:41:55.150 --> 00:41:58.450
into that athletic
field, how do we get

00:41:58.450 --> 00:42:02.350
involved in supporting
women, young girls,

00:42:02.350 --> 00:42:07.060
now, so that we develop
them into parents,

00:42:07.060 --> 00:42:09.130
like you, who are
confident enough

00:42:09.130 --> 00:42:12.370
to raise their children
to grow up in this world

00:42:12.370 --> 00:42:15.730
where social media is
possibly going to tell them--

00:42:15.730 --> 00:42:16.690
do you want this job?

00:42:16.690 --> 00:42:18.820
Do you want to inspire
other people through sports?

00:42:18.820 --> 00:42:20.049
Be pretty in a picture.

00:42:20.049 --> 00:42:20.965
KATE T. PARKER: Mm-hm.

00:42:20.965 --> 00:42:22.581
Yeah, that's so hard.

00:42:22.581 --> 00:42:23.830
ANDREW FERENCE: There's like--

00:42:23.830 --> 00:42:27.079
I mean, social media
is crazy for me.

00:42:27.079 --> 00:42:28.870
Like I said, I have a
13-year-old daughter,

00:42:28.870 --> 00:42:31.730
so you see the worst of it.

00:42:31.730 --> 00:42:33.670
But there's so much good there.

00:42:33.670 --> 00:42:35.320
There's so much good.

00:42:35.320 --> 00:42:44.890
And I send her pages and posts
constantly that highlight--

00:42:44.890 --> 00:42:48.040
you know, we all skateboard,
so girls skateboarding,

00:42:48.040 --> 00:42:52.660
so a good trick, or there's
some great follows on rugby.

00:42:52.660 --> 00:42:56.230
The girls that are playing
rugby for the [INAUDIBLE]

00:42:56.230 --> 00:42:58.420
down in New Zealand, or
some of their training

00:42:58.420 --> 00:43:02.825
videos of workouts they're
doing, and your book, you know?

00:43:02.825 --> 00:43:03.700
KATE T. PARKER: Yeah.

00:43:03.700 --> 00:43:05.470
ANDREW FERENCE: When I was
introduced to Kate's work,

00:43:05.470 --> 00:43:07.490
I was like, oh, my god,
this is incredible.

00:43:07.490 --> 00:43:10.810
Bought her book, gave it to
my girls, read it with them.

00:43:10.810 --> 00:43:14.820
Our bedtime stories
are rebel girls for--

00:43:14.820 --> 00:43:15.370
you know?

00:43:15.370 --> 00:43:19.030
Like those great books
that tell stories.

00:43:19.030 --> 00:43:25.810
But sometimes those social
media platforms, I think,

00:43:25.810 --> 00:43:28.300
they can be utilized for
so much good, because you

00:43:28.300 --> 00:43:29.410
control the message.

00:43:29.410 --> 00:43:31.159
You control what you're
putting out there.

00:43:31.159 --> 00:43:38.410
So I get that, sometimes, the
really cheesy Instagram beauty

00:43:38.410 --> 00:43:41.770
model that's just doing the
empty shots, like the sport

00:43:41.770 --> 00:43:44.710
model, come on, you can tell
she doesn't play sports.

00:43:44.710 --> 00:43:46.710
Yeah, she might have
a ton of followers,

00:43:46.710 --> 00:43:49.390
but there's a huge
market for people

00:43:49.390 --> 00:43:53.380
that don't like that, that
like the real athlete.

00:43:53.380 --> 00:43:57.700
Look at cross-fit, the explosion
of the cross-fit athlete.

00:43:57.700 --> 00:43:59.910
Those are strong athletes.

00:43:59.910 --> 00:44:01.280
They have a massive following.

00:44:01.280 --> 00:44:02.510
That's a huge market.

00:44:02.510 --> 00:44:05.410
So I think that will
always exist over here,

00:44:05.410 --> 00:44:09.880
like the pure
empty beauty stuff.

00:44:09.880 --> 00:44:14.020
That's going to happen, but
there's access now for our kids

00:44:14.020 --> 00:44:17.480
and for everybody to follow
really great content, as well,

00:44:17.480 --> 00:44:19.600
and have unbelievable
role models

00:44:19.600 --> 00:44:21.330
and to actually do
that themselves.

00:44:21.330 --> 00:44:24.034
I know my daughter, when
she's doing her Instagram

00:44:24.034 --> 00:44:26.200
stuff, her big thing now,
she wants to get verified.

00:44:26.200 --> 00:44:26.440
Right?

00:44:26.440 --> 00:44:27.150
[LAUGHTER]

00:44:27.150 --> 00:44:28.311
So we have the talk.

00:44:28.311 --> 00:44:30.310
I'm like, well, you've
got to have good content.

00:44:30.310 --> 00:44:31.990
And she's actually
putting thought into,

00:44:31.990 --> 00:44:34.090
like, all right,
the stuff that we're

00:44:34.090 --> 00:44:37.330
doing for drills in the gym,
and I'm doing all these sport

00:44:37.330 --> 00:44:39.340
things, yeah, I can
build up a profile

00:44:39.340 --> 00:44:42.775
of being a strong, 13-year-old
girl doing all this cool stuff.

00:44:42.775 --> 00:44:43.650
KATE T. PARKER: Yeah.

00:44:43.650 --> 00:44:45.191
ANDREW FERENCE: And
I was like, yeah.

00:44:45.191 --> 00:44:45.752
100%.

00:44:45.752 --> 00:44:47.710
Be one of those leaders
and one of those people

00:44:47.710 --> 00:44:49.750
that can inspire other girls.

00:44:49.750 --> 00:44:51.340
Just like you follow
all these girls

00:44:51.340 --> 00:44:53.320
around the world doing
all this great stuff,

00:44:53.320 --> 00:44:55.360
people will follow you
and be inspired by you.

00:44:55.360 --> 00:44:58.360
And I just think that you can
use these platforms for so

00:44:58.360 --> 00:44:59.530
much good, as well.

00:44:59.530 --> 00:45:00.780
KATE T. PARKER: Yeah, I agree.

00:45:00.780 --> 00:45:07.450
I think the more that we put
out honest, realistic depictions

00:45:07.450 --> 00:45:13.000
of women and women athletes, I
think people respond to that.

00:45:13.000 --> 00:45:15.850
I think if you talk about--

00:45:15.850 --> 00:45:17.830
I always tell my kids,
I feel like there should

00:45:17.830 --> 00:45:21.370
be a class for
digesting social media,

00:45:21.370 --> 00:45:23.950
to recognize that's not
real, that's facetuned,

00:45:23.950 --> 00:45:29.680
that is Photoshoped,
that is not her kitchen,

00:45:29.680 --> 00:45:31.780
she's not at that
beach every day.

00:45:31.780 --> 00:45:35.390
It's like, she went once and
changed outfits 25 times.

00:45:35.390 --> 00:45:36.000
Like, yeah.

00:45:36.000 --> 00:45:40.480
So I feel like if you
put honesty out there,

00:45:40.480 --> 00:45:43.060
and you're real, and you
talk about your struggles,

00:45:43.060 --> 00:45:46.930
your failures, your victories,
people respond to that.

00:45:46.930 --> 00:45:49.930
I mean, that's who I
follow on social media

00:45:49.930 --> 00:45:55.610
is people that are real, and
honest, and post the truth.

00:45:55.610 --> 00:45:58.240
And I think, for my kids--

00:45:58.240 --> 00:45:59.950
yeah, I have a 13-year-old too.

00:45:59.950 --> 00:46:02.455
And it's hard because you
look, and you're like,

00:46:02.455 --> 00:46:05.301
I didn't know you were friends
with her, but you're posting,

00:46:05.301 --> 00:46:05.800
I love you.

00:46:05.800 --> 00:46:06.910
You're so beautiful.

00:46:06.910 --> 00:46:12.400
And you're like, OK, let's
have a conversation about what

00:46:12.400 --> 00:46:13.810
this is.

00:46:13.810 --> 00:46:16.180
But yeah, it's really
difficult. But I think the more

00:46:16.180 --> 00:46:20.740
that you can put
honesty out there,

00:46:20.740 --> 00:46:23.050
then you may not have
as many followers,

00:46:23.050 --> 00:46:30.710
but I feel like your followers
are going to be really engaged

00:46:30.710 --> 00:46:33.665
and also probably who
you want, you know?

00:46:33.665 --> 00:46:35.290
ANDREW FERENCE: That's
Ava Ference too,

00:46:35.290 --> 00:46:36.754
if you want to
give her a follow.

00:46:36.754 --> 00:46:37.670
Help her get verified.

00:46:37.670 --> 00:46:39.690
KATE T. PARKER: Or a blue check.

00:46:39.690 --> 00:46:41.190
ANDREW FERENCE:
You're welcome, Ava.

00:46:44.010 --> 00:46:48.100
AUDIENCE: So both of you have
daughters who are older than--

00:46:48.100 --> 00:46:50.090
we have a three-and-a-half
year old daughter.

00:46:50.090 --> 00:46:53.710
And we try to be very
conscious and make an effort

00:46:53.710 --> 00:46:58.780
to not comment on
appearance and not

00:46:58.780 --> 00:47:01.535
steer her in any
gender-specific direction.

00:47:01.535 --> 00:47:04.630
And Halloween this
year, she dressed up

00:47:04.630 --> 00:47:07.535
as a super monkey, which
we thought was awesome.

00:47:07.535 --> 00:47:08.034
[LAUGHTER]

00:47:08.034 --> 00:47:08.480
ANDREW FERENCE: Awesome.

00:47:08.480 --> 00:47:10.188
AUDIENCE: But then
like, every single one

00:47:10.188 --> 00:47:12.970
of her friends in pre-school
was dressed up as a princess.

00:47:12.970 --> 00:47:14.680
And then we're
starting to worry,

00:47:14.680 --> 00:47:17.470
is she going to just pick
up on this from her peers

00:47:17.470 --> 00:47:19.970
and be like, oh, this is
what I'm supposed to do?

00:47:19.970 --> 00:47:22.270
And you must have
been through this.

00:47:22.270 --> 00:47:24.250
I'm wondering if
you have advice.

00:47:24.250 --> 00:47:27.730
Can we do anything to
prevent peer pressure

00:47:27.730 --> 00:47:29.910
from just subverting
everything we've tried to do?

00:47:29.910 --> 00:47:32.850
ANDREW FERENCE: Oh, I
mean, I know that story.

00:47:32.850 --> 00:47:34.180
KATE T. PARKER: Yeah.

00:47:34.180 --> 00:47:35.330
It's pervasive.

00:47:35.330 --> 00:47:35.670
ANDREW FERENCE: Yeah.

00:47:35.670 --> 00:47:36.220
KATE T. PARKER: Yeah.

00:47:36.220 --> 00:47:38.511
ANDREW FERENCE: I always took
the approach with my kids

00:47:38.511 --> 00:47:40.840
that-- like, I grew up, I
was really into punk rock.

00:47:40.840 --> 00:47:43.106
And so I would
wear the big docs,

00:47:43.106 --> 00:47:44.980
and I had crazy haircuts,
all kinds of stuff.

00:47:44.980 --> 00:47:46.771
So I'd show them pictures
of me growing up.

00:47:46.771 --> 00:47:49.201
And I was like
the weirdo, right?

00:47:49.201 --> 00:47:50.950
But I always take that
approach with them.

00:47:50.950 --> 00:47:52.810
I'm like, you
know, what's really

00:47:52.810 --> 00:47:55.840
important is to be weird,
to own your weirdness

00:47:55.840 --> 00:47:56.620
and be different.

00:47:56.620 --> 00:47:58.330
I'm like, how are you
going to stand out

00:47:58.330 --> 00:48:02.470
from the crowd, if you want to
be special and do something?

00:48:02.470 --> 00:48:05.590
All kids have these big dreams,
and they want to do big things.

00:48:05.590 --> 00:48:08.080
And how do you say, OK, you
want to be an astronaut.

00:48:08.080 --> 00:48:08.580
Great.

00:48:08.580 --> 00:48:10.079
You realize, to be
an astronaut, you

00:48:10.079 --> 00:48:11.874
have to be different
from everybody else.

00:48:11.874 --> 00:48:12.790
You have to work hard.

00:48:12.790 --> 00:48:14.220
You have to do all these things.

00:48:14.220 --> 00:48:17.140
And being different
is actually great.

00:48:17.140 --> 00:48:20.260
So celebrating not
being part of the crowd,

00:48:20.260 --> 00:48:23.350
I totally bring out the
punk rock rah, rah speech

00:48:23.350 --> 00:48:25.900
all the time, because I
really think that it really

00:48:25.900 --> 00:48:30.070
is incredible to
stand out in a crowd,

00:48:30.070 --> 00:48:33.340
and to embrace the
differences that you bring

00:48:33.340 --> 00:48:38.515
to a room of people, and to make
yourself have a true identity.

00:48:38.515 --> 00:48:40.640
And I always kind of took
the approach too to them,

00:48:40.640 --> 00:48:43.324
I said, do you know what's a
really great compliment when

00:48:43.324 --> 00:48:45.490
somebody has to describe
you, and it's hard for them

00:48:45.490 --> 00:48:46.262
to describe you.

00:48:46.262 --> 00:48:47.470
Like it takes a lot of words.

00:48:47.470 --> 00:48:50.080
It's not just like, oh,
he's the hockey player.

00:48:50.080 --> 00:48:51.700
You know?

00:48:51.700 --> 00:48:53.960
I don't know, I don't know
if it's the perfect answer,

00:48:53.960 --> 00:48:55.459
but that's the
approach we've taken.

00:48:55.459 --> 00:48:57.970
And I think that
embracing your weirdness,

00:48:57.970 --> 00:48:59.950
and embracing your
idiosyncrasies,

00:48:59.950 --> 00:49:02.650
and all these little differences
you have from the group,

00:49:02.650 --> 00:49:05.720
if you can celebrate that
and say, that's your power,

00:49:05.720 --> 00:49:09.440
being different is like a
superpower, it's worked for us,

00:49:09.440 --> 00:49:09.950
I think.

00:49:09.950 --> 00:49:12.710
KATE T. PARKER: I mean, that's
exactly what we tell our kids.

00:49:12.710 --> 00:49:14.734
And that's exactly,
when I do talks

00:49:14.734 --> 00:49:15.900
to girls, that's what I say.

00:49:15.900 --> 00:49:19.914
I say, the thing that makes you
stand out, the thing that you

00:49:19.914 --> 00:49:21.830
might not be proud of
right now, but the thing

00:49:21.830 --> 00:49:24.770
that makes you
different is exactly

00:49:24.770 --> 00:49:26.240
the thing that you
need to focus on

00:49:26.240 --> 00:49:28.640
and the thing that you need
to, sort of like-- that

00:49:28.640 --> 00:49:30.844
is the thing that is
the best part about you.

00:49:30.844 --> 00:49:32.510
And you really need
to pay it attention.

00:49:32.510 --> 00:49:35.900
So if you tell her
when she shows up,

00:49:35.900 --> 00:49:38.870
and there's all princesses,
and she's the one super monkey,

00:49:38.870 --> 00:49:43.790
you should be like, oh, my
god, look at how great this is.

00:49:43.790 --> 00:49:45.380
I mean, that's a weird costume.

00:49:45.380 --> 00:49:46.415
That's awesome.

00:49:46.415 --> 00:49:47.873
ANDREW FERENCE:
That is so awesome.

00:49:47.873 --> 00:49:49.379
KATE T. PARKER: You know?

00:49:49.379 --> 00:49:51.170
I think, if she gets
the reaction from you,

00:49:51.170 --> 00:49:54.530
especially at three-and-a-half,
how cool is that,

00:49:54.530 --> 00:49:56.930
you don't look like anybody
else, look at how different,

00:49:56.930 --> 00:49:59.840
yeah, If you celebrate that,
then that will become part

00:49:59.840 --> 00:50:03.200
of what she recognizes
when she's not with you.

00:50:03.200 --> 00:50:04.580
Like oh, I'm different.

00:50:04.580 --> 00:50:05.300
That's awesome.

00:50:05.300 --> 00:50:06.925
ANDREW FERENCE: And
the best part about

00:50:06.925 --> 00:50:07.820
that, it's not a lie.

00:50:07.820 --> 00:50:08.060
KATE T. PARKER: Yeah.

00:50:08.060 --> 00:50:08.930
ANDREW FERENCE: What
was our reaction when

00:50:08.930 --> 00:50:09.846
you said super monkey?

00:50:09.846 --> 00:50:11.280
We were like, oh, sick.

00:50:11.280 --> 00:50:12.890
That's awesome.

00:50:12.890 --> 00:50:13.520
It's true.

00:50:13.520 --> 00:50:16.160
People respond positively
to those things, right?

00:50:16.160 --> 00:50:18.370
So you're not even
selling her a lie.

00:50:18.370 --> 00:50:20.686
It's the truth.

00:50:20.686 --> 00:50:21.990
AUDIENCE: Hi.

00:50:21.990 --> 00:50:24.890
So I have an older boy
and a younger daughter.

00:50:24.890 --> 00:50:26.630
She's eight months now.

00:50:26.630 --> 00:50:28.190
So she gets all
the hand-me-downs.

00:50:28.190 --> 00:50:32.330
And so obviously, a lot of it
is boyish colors, and trucks,

00:50:32.330 --> 00:50:33.365
and whatever.

00:50:33.365 --> 00:50:34.740
And so my wife is
fine with that.

00:50:34.740 --> 00:50:37.290
But I'm more of like,
you know, we have a girl,

00:50:37.290 --> 00:50:40.590
so now we can get her dresses
and lots of pink and whatnot.

00:50:40.590 --> 00:50:43.250
So I'm wondering, how much
does that really influence them

00:50:43.250 --> 00:50:44.390
as they're getting older?

00:50:44.390 --> 00:50:45.980
Or at one point,
are they just going

00:50:45.980 --> 00:50:48.380
to be like, well, I don't
care how you've dressed me

00:50:48.380 --> 00:50:50.780
in the past, I want
to be this person,

00:50:50.780 --> 00:50:52.572
and I want to dress this way.

00:50:52.572 --> 00:50:54.530
KATE T. PARKER: I'm trying
to think when they--

00:50:54.530 --> 00:50:56.990
I mean, I think my
kids were always,

00:50:56.990 --> 00:51:00.597
from when they could talk, were
always very clear about what

00:51:00.597 --> 00:51:01.430
they wanted to wear.

00:51:01.430 --> 00:51:04.910
Like this one just wanted to
wear pajamas for like two years

00:51:04.910 --> 00:51:06.020
straight.

00:51:06.020 --> 00:51:09.090
And I was like, all right.

00:51:09.090 --> 00:51:13.160
I think as long as you, when
they have a voice, that you

00:51:13.160 --> 00:51:15.320
hear their voice, and
you listen to them,

00:51:15.320 --> 00:51:20.927
and you give them the power
to, I don't want to wear that,

00:51:20.927 --> 00:51:22.010
or I do want to wear pink.

00:51:22.010 --> 00:51:22.926
Like that's the thing.

00:51:22.926 --> 00:51:25.160
I don't have an issue with pink.

00:51:25.160 --> 00:51:27.050
I don't an issue
with princesses.

00:51:27.050 --> 00:51:30.500
It's just, if that's
what you want to do.

00:51:30.500 --> 00:51:31.730
I love pink.

00:51:31.730 --> 00:51:33.302
If you want to wear that, great.

00:51:33.302 --> 00:51:34.760
But if you don't
want to wear that,

00:51:34.760 --> 00:51:36.920
I just don't feel like
you should be shoehorned

00:51:36.920 --> 00:51:39.770
into it, as a girl or a boy.

00:51:39.770 --> 00:51:43.130
But yeah, I think
as long as when

00:51:43.130 --> 00:51:48.200
they have a decision making and
they're making their decisions,

00:51:48.200 --> 00:51:50.640
as long as you are
listening to that--

00:51:50.640 --> 00:51:53.150
but now, I mean,
when they're babies,

00:51:53.150 --> 00:51:55.670
you can kind of-- that's like,
you have a very small window

00:51:55.670 --> 00:51:59.015
of you can make them look like--

00:51:59.015 --> 00:52:02.461
put them in a monkey
costume, or whatever.

00:52:02.461 --> 00:52:02.960
But yeah.

00:52:02.960 --> 00:52:06.620
So I think as long as
when they have a voice,

00:52:06.620 --> 00:52:08.457
you start to listen to
it, that's important.

00:52:08.457 --> 00:52:10.248
ANDREW FERENCE: Yeah,
we've done everything

00:52:10.248 --> 00:52:12.780
from Disney princesses-- and
I mean now, like one day,

00:52:12.780 --> 00:52:14.630
it'll be the unicorn onesie.

00:52:14.630 --> 00:52:18.140
And the next day, it's like
the Thrasher skateboard hoodie.

00:52:18.140 --> 00:52:20.750
It's just, they have their
arsenal for whatever mood

00:52:20.750 --> 00:52:23.211
they're in, or whatever
they want to be that day.

00:52:23.211 --> 00:52:23.710
Right?

00:52:23.710 --> 00:52:26.510
But I mean, yeah, their voice.

00:52:26.510 --> 00:52:27.560
Let them drive the bus.

00:52:27.560 --> 00:52:28.130
KATE T. PARKER: Yeah.

00:52:28.130 --> 00:52:29.560
ANDREW FERENCE: When
they're young, I don't know.

00:52:29.560 --> 00:52:29.780
KATE T. PARKER: Yeah.

00:52:29.780 --> 00:52:30.320
ANDREW FERENCE: I
can't even think--

00:52:30.320 --> 00:52:30.970
I can't even remember what we--

00:52:30.970 --> 00:52:32.870
I think we did girl's
clothes, or whatever.

00:52:32.870 --> 00:52:34.290
KATE T. PARKER: Yeah,
we did girl-- yeah.

00:52:34.290 --> 00:52:35.240
ANDREW FERENCE:
It's not poisonous.

00:52:35.240 --> 00:52:35.660
KATE T. PARKER: Yeah.

00:52:35.660 --> 00:52:36.160
Yes.

00:52:36.160 --> 00:52:37.460
[LAUGHTER]

00:52:37.460 --> 00:52:39.418
ANDREW FERENCE: But yeah,
just like everything.

00:52:39.418 --> 00:52:40.857
Yeah, I don't know.

00:52:40.857 --> 00:52:42.440
I never put that
much thought into it,

00:52:42.440 --> 00:52:44.642
but we always let them pick
what they want to wear.

00:52:44.642 --> 00:52:46.100
KATE T. PARKER:
No, but I get that.

00:52:46.100 --> 00:52:47.430
I remember when I--

00:52:47.430 --> 00:52:50.930
because my oldest was
bald for two years.

00:52:50.930 --> 00:52:53.375
I would always get upset
when somebody would

00:52:53.375 --> 00:52:54.650
be like, oh, what's his name?

00:52:54.650 --> 00:52:58.640
And I'm like, oh, my god,
it's a girl, obviously.

00:52:58.640 --> 00:53:01.340
But I get it, if you're
constantly saying,

00:53:01.340 --> 00:53:04.100
oh, no, this is a girl,
because she's maybe in blues,

00:53:04.100 --> 00:53:04.840
or whatever.

00:53:04.840 --> 00:53:07.940
But yeah, I think now,
do whatever you want.

00:53:07.940 --> 00:53:09.214
AUDIENCE: Thanks.

00:53:09.214 --> 00:53:09.880
AUDIENCE: Great.

00:53:09.880 --> 00:53:12.530
I know we're close on time,
but just a quick question.

00:53:12.530 --> 00:53:15.410
Thank you guys, again,
for coming again.

00:53:15.410 --> 00:53:17.940
So twofold question.

00:53:17.940 --> 00:53:22.730
The first is, I know
working for the NHL, Andrew,

00:53:22.730 --> 00:53:26.720
I am really curious, especially
talking about your work

00:53:26.720 --> 00:53:29.420
with youth and how you're
looking to promote the game

00:53:29.420 --> 00:53:32.330
and grow the game, what the
responsibilities you think of

00:53:32.330 --> 00:53:35.870
are professional bodies
and governing bodies

00:53:35.870 --> 00:53:40.940
for women's youth
specifically, as well.

00:53:40.940 --> 00:53:43.010
I know in general,
just the access

00:53:43.010 --> 00:53:46.220
to resources for youth
sport, especially the NHL

00:53:46.220 --> 00:53:48.060
as a men's league--

00:53:48.060 --> 00:53:50.840
there's a separate NWHL--

00:53:50.840 --> 00:53:52.640
how do you guys view
your responsibility

00:53:52.640 --> 00:53:54.848
and the responsibility of
governing bodies in general

00:53:54.848 --> 00:53:58.660
towards promoting sports
equally between genders?

00:53:58.660 --> 00:54:02.330
And then sequentially,
I think that there's

00:54:02.330 --> 00:54:05.760
a pretty wide consensus
now, like "Strong

00:54:05.760 --> 00:54:08.640
is the New Pretty," women
or girls specifically,

00:54:08.640 --> 00:54:11.106
should be doing sports
and can do anything.

00:54:11.106 --> 00:54:13.230
But a lot of that perception--
and you pointed out,

00:54:13.230 --> 00:54:16.260
Kate-- around puberty,
things start to change a lot.

00:54:16.260 --> 00:54:18.600
And access and
participation in sports

00:54:18.600 --> 00:54:22.900
precipitously drops off, once
girls hit puberty and hit 18.

00:54:22.900 --> 00:54:24.630
So I just wanted to
get your perspective

00:54:24.630 --> 00:54:27.240
on both governing
body responsibilities

00:54:27.240 --> 00:54:29.370
and professional body
responsibilities,

00:54:29.370 --> 00:54:31.130
as well as what
the future of-- you

00:54:31.130 --> 00:54:34.870
know, you're a good strong girl,
but be a strong woman later--

00:54:34.870 --> 00:54:37.709
and how you see that transition.

00:54:37.709 --> 00:54:39.000
ANDREW FERENCE: You're bang on.

00:54:39.000 --> 00:54:40.780
I think there is a
massive responsibility.

00:54:40.780 --> 00:54:43.950
And I think that,
for the most part,

00:54:43.950 --> 00:54:48.270
we're taking our first strides
on deliberately supporting

00:54:48.270 --> 00:54:49.650
female-specific hockey.

00:54:52.180 --> 00:54:53.880
Well, just a couple
weeks ago, we

00:54:53.880 --> 00:54:56.380
supported Hayley
Wickenheiser's tournament.

00:54:56.380 --> 00:55:00.480
She's one of the greatest hockey
players of all time, Canadian.

00:55:00.480 --> 00:55:03.270
She runs an all-girls
hockey festival.

00:55:03.270 --> 00:55:06.210
And so the way we approach
it is, it's not just a hockey

00:55:06.210 --> 00:55:09.060
tournament where they
go play the games

00:55:09.060 --> 00:55:11.400
and then get the
medals and stuff.

00:55:11.400 --> 00:55:13.020
What she does is she
has hockey games,

00:55:13.020 --> 00:55:15.390
but then she has all
this off-ice activity.

00:55:15.390 --> 00:55:17.370
So you have women
empowerment sessions,

00:55:17.370 --> 00:55:19.200
and you have sports
sampling where

00:55:19.200 --> 00:55:23.010
you can go try wrestling
with the female Olympian

00:55:23.010 --> 00:55:26.010
wrestler who won a gold medal.

00:55:26.010 --> 00:55:27.900
She had the prime
minister's wife

00:55:27.900 --> 00:55:30.180
come in and give a panel
on the power of women

00:55:30.180 --> 00:55:31.290
involved in sport.

00:55:31.290 --> 00:55:34.710
And so these girls are coming
to this hockey tournament,

00:55:34.710 --> 00:55:36.480
and yeah, they're
playing hockey,

00:55:36.480 --> 00:55:40.140
but then they're at the
arena the entire day

00:55:40.140 --> 00:55:43.650
doing all these other
really powerful things

00:55:43.650 --> 00:55:45.270
and having this
great experience,

00:55:45.270 --> 00:55:47.040
while playing hockey.

00:55:47.040 --> 00:55:50.770
So at the NHL level, we look
at things like that and say,

00:55:50.770 --> 00:55:53.790
100%, this is what
we have to support.

00:55:53.790 --> 00:55:56.910
Like I said, we're not
trying to build necessarily

00:55:56.910 --> 00:55:59.250
the next generation
of NHL players,

00:55:59.250 --> 00:56:01.560
we're trying to build the
next generation of people

00:56:01.560 --> 00:56:02.790
that just love hockey.

00:56:02.790 --> 00:56:07.200
And obviously, from a business
decision, girls, boys,

00:56:07.200 --> 00:56:11.400
everybody, we want to watch, and
be a fan, and enjoy the game.

00:56:11.400 --> 00:56:14.080
So obviously, from a business
sense, it makes a lot of sense.

00:56:14.080 --> 00:56:18.010
I mean, it'd be crazy to
ignore the female market,

00:56:18.010 --> 00:56:21.350
but just because it's the
right thing to do, as well.

00:56:21.350 --> 00:56:25.800
Our sport, the
participation levels

00:56:25.800 --> 00:56:29.040
in both Canada and
the US, we've actually

00:56:29.040 --> 00:56:31.190
gone up in the last couple
of years only because

00:56:31.190 --> 00:56:33.160
of female participation.

00:56:33.160 --> 00:56:37.170
Girls hockey is taking off
like crazy all over the place--

00:56:37.170 --> 00:56:41.370
California, even down
in Texas and Las Vegas,

00:56:41.370 --> 00:56:42.660
now that they have a team.

00:56:42.660 --> 00:56:44.340
It's insane when
you see the growth

00:56:44.340 --> 00:56:47.910
in the female part of our game.

00:56:47.910 --> 00:56:50.130
And really, for
the most part, we

00:56:50.130 --> 00:56:52.980
have some clubs that are doing
incredible things at a city

00:56:52.980 --> 00:56:53.484
level.

00:56:53.484 --> 00:56:54.900
But as the NHL,
like I said, we're

00:56:54.900 --> 00:56:58.440
in our first strides of
deliberately supporting

00:56:58.440 --> 00:57:02.670
female hockey and giving
them resources and supporting

00:57:02.670 --> 00:57:03.450
their tournaments.

00:57:03.450 --> 00:57:06.750
And even just yesterday,
for the last two days,

00:57:06.750 --> 00:57:09.570
actually, at headquarters,
we had 12 powerful women

00:57:09.570 --> 00:57:12.240
from across our sport,
from broadcasting,

00:57:12.240 --> 00:57:18.660
to executive levels,
to players, obviously.

00:57:18.660 --> 00:57:21.690
But we're putting together
a strong advisory panel,

00:57:21.690 --> 00:57:25.260
specific to help guide
us down that path.

00:57:25.260 --> 00:57:27.390
My department's majority female.

00:57:27.390 --> 00:57:28.350
My boss is female.

00:57:28.350 --> 00:57:30.960
So I think that
that representation

00:57:30.960 --> 00:57:34.710
is incredibly important at an
executive level of the NHL.

00:57:34.710 --> 00:57:36.120
That's different.

00:57:36.120 --> 00:57:38.640
Over the past few years
of our commissioner

00:57:38.640 --> 00:57:40.620
bringing in strong
female leaders

00:57:40.620 --> 00:57:44.340
into the highest
positions within NHL

00:57:44.340 --> 00:57:48.591
to help make these decisions,
that's massive progress,

00:57:48.591 --> 00:57:49.090
I think.

00:57:49.090 --> 00:57:53.190
And it's because of, I think,
that responsibility, but also

00:57:53.190 --> 00:57:55.621
good business.

00:57:55.621 --> 00:57:57.620
KATE T. PARKER: Oh, and
then the second question

00:57:57.620 --> 00:58:01.730
about the drop off
of girls in puberty

00:58:01.730 --> 00:58:04.280
from sports, which is huge.

00:58:04.280 --> 00:58:09.950
And I don't know how to fix
it, but that's something

00:58:09.950 --> 00:58:13.387
that I definitely, moving
forward in 2019 as part

00:58:13.387 --> 00:58:15.470
of "Strong is the New
Pretty", that we are looking

00:58:15.470 --> 00:58:17.210
to give back in that way.

00:58:19.730 --> 00:58:23.440
I mean, it could be
something simple and as easy

00:58:23.440 --> 00:58:26.180
as some girls don't
have a sports bra,

00:58:26.180 --> 00:58:29.540
and that is why they
are not participating.

00:58:29.540 --> 00:58:31.970
Or just like there's
these certain barriers

00:58:31.970 --> 00:58:36.620
that, because at that point
it gets really competitive,

00:58:36.620 --> 00:58:39.470
and its travel,
and it's expensive,

00:58:39.470 --> 00:58:42.620
but there's a lot of different
barriers that, I think,

00:58:42.620 --> 00:58:44.510
if we can keep our
girls in sports,

00:58:44.510 --> 00:58:49.670
I feel like it's such a
huge part of confidence

00:58:49.670 --> 00:58:53.780
and self-worth that they
need at that age, more

00:58:53.780 --> 00:58:55.700
than any other age.

00:58:55.700 --> 00:58:58.880
And yeah, it's something
that I would really

00:58:58.880 --> 00:59:02.030
personally like to focus
on, keeping girls in sports.

00:59:02.030 --> 00:59:04.490
And there's so many different
reasons why they're dropping

00:59:04.490 --> 00:59:08.900
out, that if there
is simple Band-Aids,

00:59:08.900 --> 00:59:14.120
we can get all of the girls
in Georgia sports bras,

00:59:14.120 --> 00:59:18.709
or pedometers, or something
like that, I would--

00:59:18.709 --> 00:59:19.250
I don't know.

00:59:19.250 --> 00:59:21.350
I think it's something
that we need to address,

00:59:21.350 --> 00:59:25.840
because it definitely
affects strong women.

00:59:25.840 --> 00:59:29.570
I played through college
and got so much out of it.

00:59:29.570 --> 00:59:33.620
And it's such a huge part of
my work ethic today and sense

00:59:33.620 --> 00:59:39.350
of confidence, I think, that
it's sort of like a tragedy

00:59:39.350 --> 00:59:42.230
if people miss out on
that, if they love a sport.

00:59:42.230 --> 00:59:44.052
That's the thing.

00:59:44.052 --> 00:59:45.260
It doesn't have to be sports.

00:59:45.260 --> 00:59:47.570
Whatever it is,
just find a passion

00:59:47.570 --> 00:59:49.790
and invest yourself in it.

00:59:49.790 --> 00:59:53.120
And I think it's just opening
the pathways for girls

00:59:53.120 --> 00:59:56.120
to figure out what that is,
and then staying with it

00:59:56.120 --> 00:59:58.100
and giving them the
avenue, and the path,

00:59:58.100 --> 01:00:00.460
and the support to continue
with whatever they love.

